# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: technical-alliance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The oldest city in New York, the City of Albany is the economic and cultural core of New York State's Capital District.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Capital District is a metropolitan area including the nearby cities and suburbs of Colonie, Troy, Schenectady, and Saratoga Springs.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] With an estimated 1.3 million residents, the Capital District is one of the most populous metropolitan areas and is the fastest-growing region in Upstate New York.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The area that ultimately became Albany was originally inhabited by Algonquian-speaking Mohicans.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The area was settled by Dutch colonists, who built Fort Nassau in 1614 for fur trading and Fort Orange in 1624.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 1664, the English took over the Dutch settlements, renaming the city "Albany" in honor of the Scottish title of the Duke of York (later James II of England and Ireland and James VII of Scotland): the Duke of Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The city was officially chartered in 1686 under English rule.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] It became the capital of New York in 1797 after the formation of the United States.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is the oldest surviving settlement of the original British Thirteen Colonies north of Virginia.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In the late 18th century and throughout most of the 19th, Albany was a center of trade and transportation.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The city lies toward the north end of the navigable Hudson River.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] It was the original eastern terminus of the Erie Canal and was home to some of the earliest railroads in the world.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1920s, a powerful political machine controlled by the Democratic Party emerged in Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's population shrank because of urban sprawl and suburbanization in the latter part of the 20th century.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1990s, the New York State Legislature approved for the city a US$234 million building and renovation plan, which spurred downtown redevelopment.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Since 2020, the economy of Albany and the surrounding Capital District has been directed toward artificial intelligence, AI-based photonics, quantum computing hardware manufacturing, nanotechnology, and digital electronics.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Hudson River area was originally inhabited by Algonquian-speaking Mohicans, who called it *Pempotowwuthut-Muhhcanneuw*, meaning "the fireplace of the Mohican nation".
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Based to the west along the Mohawk River, the Iroquoian-speaking Mohawk called it *skahnéhtati*, also transliterated to Sche-negh-ta-da, "through the pine woods", referring to the path they took there.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] According to Hendrick Aupaumut, the Mohicans came to the area from the north and the west.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] They settled along the Mahicannituck River, which is now called the Hudson River, and called themselves the *Muh-he-con-neok*, the "People of the Waters That Are Never Still".
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Mohawks, one of the Five Nations of the Iroquois Confederacy, were based in the Mohawk valley and noted for their fur trading and their access to trade between the Iroquois and other nations.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Mohawk became strong trading partners with the Dutch and English.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] It is likely that the area was visited by European fur traders perhaps as early as 1540, but the extent and duration of those visits are unclear.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Permanent European claims began when Englishman Henry Hudson, exploring for the Dutch East India Company on the *Half Moon* (Dutch: *Halve Maen*), reached the area in 1609, claiming it for the United Netherlands.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 1614, Hendrick Christiaensen built Fort Nassau on Castle Island (now called Port of Albany), in the Hudson River.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The fort acted as a fur-trading post and was the first documented European structure in present-day Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Commencement of the fur trade provoked hostility from the French colony in Canada and among the natives, all of whom vied to control the trade.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 1618, a flood ruined Fort Nassau, but the Dutch replaced it with Fort Orange on the mainland in 1624.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Both forts were named in honor of the leading family of the Dutch Revolt, members of the House of Orange-Nassau.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Fort Orange and the surrounding area were incorporated as the village of Beverwijck (English: Beaverwick or Beaver District) in 1652, and the city of Albany in 1686.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In these early decades of trade, the Dutch, Mohican, and Mohawk developed relations that reflected differences among their three cultures.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is one of the oldest surviving European settlements from the original Thirteen Colonies and the longest continuously chartered city in the United States.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] When New Netherland was captured by the English in 1664, the name was changed from *Beverwijck* to *Albany* in honor of Prince James, Duke of Albany (later King James VII/II).
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Duke of Albany was a Scottish title given since 1398, generally to a younger son of the King of Scots.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The name is ultimately derived from *Alba*, the Gaelic name for Scotland.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Dutch briefly regained Albany in August 1673 and renamed the city *Willemstadt*; the English took permanent possession in 1674 with the Treaty of Westminster.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was formally chartered as a municipality by provincial Governor Thomas Dongan on July 22, 1686.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Dongan Charter was virtually identical in content to the charter awarded to the city of New York three months earlier.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Dongan created Albany as a strip of land 1 mile (1.6 km) wide and 16 miles (26 km) long.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Over the years Albany would lose much of the land to the west and annex land to the north and south.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] At this point, Albany had a population of about 500 people.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 1754, representatives of seven British North American colonies met in the *Stadt Huys*, Albany's city hall, for the Albany Congress; Benjamin Franklin of Pennsylvania presented the Albany Plan of Union there, which was the first formal proposal to unite the colonies.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Although it was never adopted by Parliament, it was an important precursor to the United States Constitution.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The same year, the French and Indian War, the fourth in a series of wars dating back to 1689, began.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] It ended in 1763 with French defeat, resolving a situation that had been a constant threat to Albany and held back its growth.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Tories and prisoners of war were often jailed in the *Stadt Huys* alongside common criminals.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 1776, Albany native Philip Livingston signed the Declaration of Independence.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] During and after the Revolutionary War, Albany County saw a great increase in real estate transactions.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] After the 1777 colonial victory at the Battle of Saratoga, the upper Hudson Valley was generally at peace as the war raged on elsewhere.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Prosperity was soon seen all over Upstate New York.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Migrants from Vermont and Connecticut began flowing in, noting the advantages of living on the Hudson and trading at Albany, while being only a few days' sail from New York City.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany reported a population of 3,498 in the first national census in 1790, an increase of almost 700% since its chartering.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] On November 17, 1793, fire broke out at a stable belonging to Leonard Gansevoort, destroying 26 homes on Broadway, Maiden Lane, James Street, and State Street.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Three were arrested and charged with arson: Pompey, a man belonging to Matthew Visscher; Dinah, a 14-year-old girl belonging to Volkert P.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Douw; and Bet, a 12-year-old girl belonging to Philip S.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] On January 6, 1794, the three were sentenced to death.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Governor George Clinton issued a temporary stay of execution, but Dinah and Bet were executed by hanging on March 14, and Pompey on April 11, 1794.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 1797, the state capital was moved permanently to Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] From statehood to this date, the Legislature had frequently moved the state capital between Albany, Kingston, Poughkeepsie, and the city of New York.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is the tenth-oldest state capital in the United States and the second-oldest city that is a state capital, after Santa Fe, New Mexico.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany has been a center of transportation for much of its history.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In the late 18th and early 19th centuries, Albany saw development of the turnpike and by 1815, Albany was the turnpike center of the state.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The development of Simeon De Witt's gridded block system in 1794—which renamed streets that had originally named after the British royal family with names of birds and mammals instead—was intersected by these major arterials coming out of Albany, cutting through the city at unexpected angles.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The construction of the turnpike, in conjunction with canal and railroad systems, made Albany the hub of transportation for pioneers going to Buffalo and the Michigan Territory in the early and mid-19th century.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 1807, Robert Fulton initiated a steamboat line from New York City to Albany, the first successful enterprise of its kind anywhere in the world.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] By 1810, with 10,763 people, Albany was the tenth-largest urban place in the nation.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The town and village north of Albany known as "the Colonie" was annexed in 1815.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 1825 the Erie Canal was completed, forming a continuous water route from the Great Lakes to New York City.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Unlike the current Barge Canal, which ends at nearby Waterford, the original Erie Canal ended at Albany; Lock 1 was north of Colonie Street.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Canal emptied into a 32-acre (13 ha) man-made lagoon called the Albany Basin, which was Albany's main port from 1825 until the Port of Albany-Rensselaer opened in 1932.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 1829, while working as a professor at the Albany Academy, Joseph Henry, widely regarded as "the foremost American scientist of the 19th century", built the first electric motor.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Three years later, he discovered electromagnetic self-induction (the SI unit for which is now the henry).
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] He went on to be the first Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1830 and 1840 censuses, Albany was ranked as the ninth-largest urban place in the nation; it dropped back to tenth in 1850.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] This was the last time the city was one of the top ten largest urban places in the nation.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany also has significant history with rail transport, as the location of two major regional railroad headquarters.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Delaware and Hudson Railway was headquartered in Albany at what is now the SUNY System Administration Building.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 1853, Erastus Corning, a noted industrialist and Albany's mayor from 1834 to 1837, consolidated ten railroads stretching from Albany to Buffalo into the New York Central Railroad (NYCRR), headquartered in Albany until Cornelius Vanderbilt moved it to New York City in 1867.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] One of the ten companies that formed the NYCRR was the Mohawk and Hudson Railroad, which was the first railroad in the state and the first successful steam railroad running regularly scheduled service in the country.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] While the key to Albany's economic prosperity in the 19th century was transportation, industry and business also played a role.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Largely thanks to the city's Dutch and German roots, beer was one of its biggest commodities.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Beverwyck Brewery, originally known as Quinn and Nolan (Nolan being mayor of Albany 1878–1883), was the last remaining brewer from that time when it closed in 1972.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The city's location at the east end of the Erie Canal gave it unparalleled access to both raw products and a captive customer base in the west.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was known for its publishing houses, and to some extent, still is.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was second only to Boston in the number of books produced for most of the 19th century.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Iron foundries in both the north and south ends of the city attracted thousands of immigrants to the city for industrial jobs.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Intricate wrought-iron details constructed in those years remain visible on what are now historic buildings.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The iron industry waned by the 1890s due to increased costs associated with a newly unionized workforce and the opening of mines in the Mesabi Range in Minnesota.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's other major exports during the 18th and 19th centuries were furs, wheat, meat, and lumber.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] By 1865, there were almost 4,000 saw mills in the Albany area and the Albany Lumber District was the largest lumber market in the nation.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The city was also home to a number of banks.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Bank of Albany (1792–1861) was the second chartered bank in New York.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The city was the original home of the Albank (founded in 1820 as the Albany Savings Bank), KeyBank (founded in 1825 as the Commercial Bank of Albany), and Norstar Bank (founded as the State Bank of Albany in 1803).
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] American Express was founded in Albany in 1850 as an express mail business.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 1871, the northwestern portion of Albany—west from Magazine Street—was annexed to the neighboring town of Guilderland after the town of Watervliet refused annexation of the territory.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In return for this loss, portions of Bethlehem and Watervliet were added to Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Part of the land annexed to Guilderland was ceded back to Albany in 1910, setting up the current western border.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The train carrying the body of slain President Abraham Lincoln came through Albany on the way to Illinois and the ghostly image of that train remains.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany opened one of the first commercial airports in the world, and the first municipal airport in the United States, in 1908.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Originally on a polo field on Loudon Road, it moved to Westerlo Island in 1909 and remained there until 1928.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Albany Municipal Airport—jointly owned by the city and county—was moved to its current location in Colonie in 1928.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] By 1916 Albany's northern and southern borders reached their modern courses; Westerlo Island, to the south, became the second-to-last annexation, which occurred in 1926.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Erastus Corning 2nd, arguably Albany's most notable mayor (and great-grandson of the former mayor of the same name), was elected in 1941.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] While Corning brought stability to the office of mayor, it is said even those who admire him greatly cannot come up with a sizable list of "major concrete Corning achievements." Corning is given credit for saving—albeit somewhat unintentionally—much of Albany's historic architecture.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] During the 1950s and 1960s, a time when federal aid for urban renewal was plentiful, Albany did not have growth in its economy or infrastructure.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] It lost more than 20 percent of its population during the Corning years, as people moved to newer housing in the suburbs, followed by most of the downtown businesses moving there as well.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] While cities across the country grappled with similar issues, the problems were magnified in Albany: interference from the Democratic political machine hindered progress considerably.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 1960, the mayor sold the city's stake in the airport to the county, citing budget issues.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] It was known from then on as Albany County Airport until a massive upgrade and modernization project between 1996 and 1998, when it was rebranded Albany International Airport.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Governor Nelson Rockefeller (1959–1973) (R) tried to stimulate the city with new monumental architecture and large, government-sponsored building projects; he drove construction of the Empire State Plaza, SUNY Albany's uptown campus, and much of the W.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Averell Harriman State Office Building Campus.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany County Republican Chairman Joseph C.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Frangella once quipped, "Governor Rockefeller was the best mayor Albany ever had." Corning, although opposed to the project, was responsible for negotiating the payment plan for the Empire State Plaza.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Rockefeller did not want to be limited by the Legislature's power of the purse, so Corning devised a plan to have the county pay for the construction and have the state sign a lease-ownership agreement.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The state paid off the bonds until 2004.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] It was Rockefeller's only viable option, and he agreed.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Due to the clout Corning gained from the situation, he gained inclusion of the State Museum, a convention center, and a restaurant, back in the plans—ideas which Rockefeller had originally vetoed.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The county gained $35 million in fees and the city received $13 million for lost tax revenue.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Having the state offices in the city enabled it to keep good jobs and retain middle-class residents.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Another major project of the 1960s and 1970s was the construction of Interstate 787 and the South Mall Arterial.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] A proposed Mid-Crosstown Arterial never came to fruition.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] One of the project's main results was separating the city from the Hudson River.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] When Corning died in 1983, Thomas Whalen assumed the mayorship and was reelected twice.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] He encouraged redevelopment of historic structures and helped attract federal dollars earmarked for that purpose.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] What Corning had saved from destruction, Whalen refurbished for continued and new uses.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Mayor's Office of Special Events was created in an effort to increase the number of festivals and artistic events in the city, including a year-long *Dongan Charter* tricentennial celebration in 1986.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Whalen is credited for an "unparalleled cycle of commercial investment and development" in Albany due to his "aggressive business development programs".
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Prior to the recession of the 1990s, downtown Albany was home to four Fortune 500 companies.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] After the death of Corning and the retirement of Congressman Sam Stratton, the political environment changed.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Long-term office holders became rare in the 1980s.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Local media began following the drama surrounding county politics (specifically that of the newly created county executive position); the loss of Corning (and eventually the machine) led to a lack of interest in city politics.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The election of Gerald Jennings was a surprise, and he served as mayor from 1994 until his retirement at the end of 2013.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] His tenure essentially ended the political machine that had been in place since the 1920s.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Many state workers were relocated from the Harriman State Office Campus to downtown, helping its retail businesses and vitality.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The first decade of the 21st century saw a real possibility for a long-discussed and controversial Albany Convention Center; it opened in 2017 with the goal of making Albany a viable location for large events hosted by statewide organizations.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany remains an important location for business presence, given its role as de facto seat of Tech Valley and being home to the state capitol.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Fortune 500 companies with offices in Albany include American Express, J.P.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Morgan and Chase, Merrill Lynch, General Electric, Verizon, Goldman Sachs, International Paper, and Key Bank.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany won the All-America City Award in both 1991 and 2009.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] is located at the extreme right of the image.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is about 135 miles (217 km) north of New York City on the Hudson River.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] It has a total area of 21.8 square miles (56 km2), of which 21.4 square miles (55 km2) is land and 0.4 square miles (1.0 km2) (1.8%) is water.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The city is bordered on the north by the town of Colonie (along with the village of Menands), on the west by the town of Guilderland, and on the south by the town of Bethlehem.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The former Foxes Creek, Beaver Kill, and Rutten Kill were diverted underground in the 19th century.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] There are four lakes within city limits: Buckingham Lake; Rensselaer Lake at the mouth of the Patroon Creek; Tivoli Lake, which was formed as a reservoir and once connected to the Patroon Creek; and Washington Park Lake, which was formed by damming the Beaver Kill.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The highest natural point in Albany is a USGS benchmark near the Loudonville Reservoir off Birch Hill Road, at 378 feet (115 m) above sea level.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The lowest point is at the Hudson River—which is still technically an estuary at Albany and is affected by the Atlantic tide—at an average of 2 feet (0.61 m) above sea level at low tide and 4 feet (1.2 m) at high tide.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The interior of Albany consists of rolling hills which were once part of the Albany Pine Bush, an area of pitch pine and scrub oak, and has arid, sandy soil that is a remnant of the ancient Lake Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Due to development, the Pine Bush has shrunk from an original 25,000 to 6,000 acres (10,100 to 2,400 ha) today.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] A preserve was set up by the State Legislature in 1988 and is on the city's western edge, spilling into Guilderland and Colonie; it is the only sizable inland pine barrens sand dune ecosystem in the United States, and is home to many endangered species, including the Karner Blue butterfly.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is in the humid continental climate zone (Köppen climate classification: Dfa), and features cold, snowy winters, and hot, humid summers; the city experiences four distinct seasons.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is in plant hardiness zone 6a near downtown and along the shore of the Hudson and 5b at its western end.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany receives 40.7 inches (1,030 mm) of precipitation per year, with 138 days of at least 0.01 in (0.25 mm) of precipitation each year.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Snowfall is significant, totaling 59.4 inches (151 cm) per season, but with less accumulation than the lake effect areas to the north and west, as it is farther from Lake Ontario.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] However, Albany is close enough to the Atlantic coast to receive heavy snow from Nor'easters and the city occasionally receives Alberta clippers.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Winters can be very cold with fluctuating conditions; temperatures drop to 0 °F (−18 °C) or below on nine nights per annum.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Summers in Albany can contain stretches of excessive heat and humidity, with temperatures of 90 °F (32 °C) or hotter on nine days per year.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Due to the variety of its communities, Albany is often called a "city of neighborhoods." The neighborhoods of Albany include Arbor Hill; Center Square, "[an] eclectic mix of residential and commercial [buildings], including bars, night clubs, restaurants, and stores"; Pine Hills; and the South End.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Historically, Albany's population has been mixed.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] First dominated by Mohican and Mohawk people, then Dutch and Germans, it was overtaken by the British in the early 19th century.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Irish immigrants soon outnumbered most other ethnicities by the mid-19th century, and were followed by Italians and Poles.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In the mid-to-late 20th century, the African-American population increased with thousands of people from the rural South, as part of the Great Migration.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Until after the Revolution, Albany's population consisted mostly of ethnic Dutch descendants.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Settlers migrating from New England tipped the balance toward British ethnicity in the early 19th century.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Jobs on the turnpikes, canals, and railroads attracted floods of Irish immigrants in the early 19th century, especially in the 1840s during the Great Famine, solidifying the city's Irish base.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Michael Nolan became Albany's first Irish Catholic mayor in 1878, two years before Boston.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Polish and Italian immigrants began arriving in Albany in the wave of immigration in the latter part of the 19th century.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Their numbers were smaller than in many other eastern cities mainly because most had found manufacturing jobs at General Electric in Schenectady.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Jewish community had been established early, with Sephardic Jewish members as part of the Beverwijck community.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Its population rose during the late 19th century, when many Ashkenazi Jews immigrated from eastern Europe.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In that period, there was also an influx of Chinese and east Asian immigrants, who settled in the downtown section of the city.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Many of their descendants have since moved to suburban areas.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Asian immigration all but halted after the Immigration Act of 1924.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany saw its last large immigration pattern as part of the Great Migration when many African Americans moved there from the American South before and after World War I to fill industrial positions and find other opportunities.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In the early years, African-Americans lived together with Italians, Jews, and other immigrants in the South End, where housing was older and less expensive.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The black community has grown as a proportion of the population since then; African Americans made up three percent of the city's population in 1950, six percent in 1960, 12 percent in 1970, and 30 percent in 2010.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The change in proportion is related mostly to middle-class white families moving to the suburbs and black families remaining within city limits during the same time period.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Since 2007, the number of Burmese refugees to Albany has increased.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Burmese refugee community consists mostly of people of Karen ethnicity.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] An estimated 5,000 Burmese refugees reside in Albany as of January 2015.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Like most cities of comparable age and size, Albany has well-established Orthodox Christian, Roman Catholic, Protestant, and Jewish communities.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is home to the oldest Christian congregation in Upstate New York and the Mother Churches of two Christian dioceses.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] As of June 2010, eight churches or religious buildings in the city were listed on the National Register of Historic Places, one of which—St.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Peter's Episcopal Church on State Street—is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Established in 1642, the congregation of the First Church in Albany (Reformed), also known as the North Dutch Church (on North Pearl Street), is the second-oldest Reformed Church in America.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2023, the city was home to twelve Catholic churches and four Episcopal churches.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Despite its history of Christendom, in 2019 the Albany-Schenectady-Troy MSA was found to be among the most post-Christian cities in the United States in a study by Christian polling firm The Barna Group.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] A significant Jewish presence has existed in Albany as early as 1658.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2010, Albany is home to two Conservative synagogues, a Chabad-Lubavitch synagogue, an Orthodox synagogue, and two Reform synagogues.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is also home to one of the few Karaite synagogues outside Israel.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2008, the total membership in Albany's synagogues was estimated at 12,000–13,000, with half the members residing outside the city.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Since the early 2000s, there has been an increase in Orthodox Jews moving to Albany from the New York Metro area, largely due to cheaper housing prices and closer walking proximity to synagogues.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Islamic community in Albany and its surrounding suburbs is represented by at least four major mosques in the region.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The Muslim population increased substantially starting in the late 2000s, with the arrival of many refugees from countries such as Iraq, Syria, and Afghanistan.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Exact numbers on religious denominations in Albany are not readily available.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Demographic statistics in the United States depend heavily on the United States Census Bureau, which cannot ask about religious affiliation as part of its decennial census.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] It does compile some national and statewide religious statistics, but these are not representative of a city the size of Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] One report from 2000 offers religious affiliations for Albany County.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] According to the data, 59.2% of Albany County residents identified as Christian: 47% are Roman Catholic, 8.4% are mainline Protestants, 2.7% are Evangelical Protestants, and 1.1% are Eastern or Oriental Orthodox Christians.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Residents who practice Judaism make up 4.2% of the population and Muslims represent 0.2%.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2020 census, Albany had a population of 99,224.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] 17.8% of residents were under the age of 18 and 13.3% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females there were 93.5 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 91.3 males age 18 and over.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] There were 42,158 households in Albany, of which 21.8% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Of all households, 22.4% were married-couple households, 29.1% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 39.5% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] About 43.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] There were 48,031 housing units, of which 12.2% were vacant.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.7% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.8%.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] According to the 2020 American Community Survey, the Latino population was: 4.57% Puerto Rican, 1.45% Dominican, .84% Ecuadorian, .77% Mexican, .69% Salvadoran, .22% Cuban.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2010 census, Albany's population density was 4,572.7 inhabitants per square mile (1,765.5/km2).
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] There were 46,362 housing units at an average density of 2,166.4 per square mile (836.5/km2); 5,205 of these units (11.2%) were vacant.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The racial makeup of the city residents was 52.3% white; 27% Black or African American; 0.06% Native American or Native Alaskan; 7.4% Asian; 0.1% Native Hawaiian or Pacific Islander; .06% from other races; and 3.6% from two or more races.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] A total of 9.2% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Non-Hispanic Whites were 52.0% of the population in 2010, compared to 87.0% in 1970.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females, there were 90.6 males.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 86.5 males.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Some 81.3% of the population had completed high school or earned an equivalency diploma.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2000 census, the top five ancestry groups in the city were African American (27%), Irish (18.1%), Italian (12.4%), German (10.4%), and English (5.2%); (33.1%) of the population reported "other ancestries".
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is home to a Triqui language-speaking community of Mexican-Americans.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] There were 40,709 households in Albany in 2000, of which 22.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 25.3% were married couples living together, 16.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 54.8% were non-families.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] 41.9% of all households were made up of individuals, and 11.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The average household size was 2.11 and the average family size was 2.95.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The median income for a household in the city in 2000 was $96,713, and the median income for a family was $100,374 (male, year-round worker) and $91,052 (female, year-round worker).
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The per capita income for the city was $73,985.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] About 16.0% of families and 21.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 28.8% of those under age 18 and 12.5% of those age 65 or over.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The rate of reported violent crimes for 2008 (1,095 incidents per 100,000 residents) were more than double the rate for similarly sized US cities.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Reported property crimes (4,669 incidents per 100,000 residents) were somewhat lower.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] With a 2013 Census-estimated population of 1.1 million, the eight county Capital District, encompassing Albany, Troy, Schenectady and Saratoga, is the third-most populous metropolitan region in the state.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Demographically speaking, the population of Albany and the Capital District mirrors the characteristics of the United States consumer population as a whole better than any other major municipality in the country.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] According to a 2004 study conducted by the Acxiom Corporation, Albany and its environs are the top-ranked standard test market for new business and retail products.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany, Rochester, and Syracuse all scored within the top five.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's violent crime rate was 10.03 per 1,000 residents in 2023, compared to 7.69 in Buffalo, 7.39 in Rochester, 8.22 in Syracuse, and 7.72 in New York City.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] New York State had statewide violent crime rate of 3.90 per 1,000 people in 2023.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's economy, along with that of the Capital District in general, is heavily dependent on government, health care, education, and more recently, technology.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Because of these typically steady economic bases, the local economy has been relatively immune to national economic recessions in the past.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 2009, more than 25 percent of the city's population worked in government-related positions.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's estimated daytime population is more than 162,000.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Companies based in Albany include Trans World Entertainment, AMRI Global and Clough Harbour.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] In 2019, Albany had the fourth-highest amount of lawyers in its employment pool (7.5 lawyers per 1,000 jobs) compared to the rest of the nation, behind Washington, D.C., Trenton, New Jersey, and New York City, respectively.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Since the 2000s, the economy of Albany and the surrounding Capital District has been directed toward high technology, a growing fourth sector of the area's economic base.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] Tech Valley is a marketing name for the eastern part of New York State, encompassing Albany, the Capital District, and the Hudson Valley.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] The area's high technology ecosystem is supported by technologically focused academic institutions including Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute and the State University of New York Polytechnic Institute.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p01] A notable video game development cluster has grown in and around Albany starting in the 2010s.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's geographic situation—roughly equidistant from New York City to the south and Montreal to the north—makes it a convenient stop for nationally touring artists and acts.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Palace Theatre and The Egg are mid-sized forums for music, theater, and spoken-word performances; the Capital Repertory Theatre is smaller.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The MVP Arena is the city's largest musical venue for nationally and internationally prominent bands.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] It also hosts trade shows, sporting events, and other large gatherings.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In recent years, the city's government has invested resources to cultivate venues and neighborhoods that attract after-hours business.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Madison Avenue, Pearl Street, Delaware Avenue and Lark Street are the most active entertainment areas in the city.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Many restaurants, clubs, and bars have opened since the mid-1990s, revitalizing areas that had once been abandoned and reclaiming old row houses, businesses, and a pump station.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Much of the bar restaurant scene features classic Irish Pubs.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Price Chopper Fabulous Fourth and Fireworks Festival at the Empire State Plaza celebrates Independence Day with musical performances and the region's largest fireworks display.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Chefs' Food & Wine Festival donates all net proceeds to deserving Albany Arts Organizations and is held the Thursday-Saturday preceding Martin Luther King Weekend.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Because of Albany's historical and political significance, the city has numerous museums, historical buildings, and historic districts.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is home to the New York State Museum, the New York State Library and the New York State Archives; all three facilities are in the Cultural Education Center at the south end of Empire State Plaza and are free to the public.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The USS *Slater* (DE-766), a decommissioned World War II destroyer escort that was restored in 1998, is a museum ship docked in the Hudson River at Quay Street.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] It is the only ship of its kind still afloat.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Heritage Area Visitors Center, at the corner of Clinton Avenue and Broadway at Quackenbush Square, hosts a museum, gift shop, and the Henry Hudson Planetarium.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In early 2012, the Irish American Heritage Museum opened in downtown Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The museum is home to exhibits highlighting the contributions of the Irish people in America.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is home to 57 listings on the National Register of Historic Places (NRHP) and five National Historic Landmarks.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Ten Broeck Mansion, a 1797 Federal-style mansion (later renovated in the Greek-Revival style) built for Abraham Ten Broeck (mayor of Albany 1779–1783 and 1796–1798) is a historic house museum and the headquarters of the Albany County Historical Association; it was added to the NRHP in 1971.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Later known as "Arbor Hill", it gave the current neighborhood its name.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has been the subject, inspiration, or location for many written and cinematic works.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Many non-fiction works have been written on the city.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] One of the city's more notable claims to fame is *Ironweed* (1983), the 1984 Pulitzer Prize-winning book by Albany native William Kennedy.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] *Ironweed* was the third in a series of books by Kennedy known as the "Albany Cycle".
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The elusive author Trevanian also grew up in Albany and wrote *The Crazyladies of Pearl Street* (2005), about a North Albany neighborhood along Pearl Street.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The book is considered a semi-autobiographical memoir.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In 1987, the film version of *Ironweed* premiered at the Palace Theatre.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The movie starred Jack Nicholson and Meryl Streep, each of whom were nominated for Academy Awards for their performances; much of the filming was done on location in Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Most recently the downtown area was the site of filming for the action-thriller *Salt*, starring Angelina Jolie, and the action-comedy *The Other Guys*, starring Will Ferrell and Mark Wahlberg.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Authors Herman Melville and Henry James lived with their families in Albany when young, before their careers.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] James identified his character Isabel Archer, the heroine of his novel *The Portrait of a Lady*, as being from Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Gregory Maguire, author of *Wicked: The Life and Times of the Wicked Witch of the West* (adapted for the Broadway hit *Wicked*), grew up in North Albany and graduated from SUNY Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Empire State Plaza, a collection of state agency office buildings, dominates almost any view of Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Built between 1965 and 1978 at the hand of Governor Nelson A.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Rockefeller and architect Wallace Harrison, the complex is a powerful example of late American modern architecture and remains a controversial building project both for displacing city residents and for its architectural style.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The most recognizable aspect of the complex is the Erastus Corning Tower, the tallest building in New York outside of New York City.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Juxtaposed at the north end of the Plaza is the 19th-century New York State Capitol, the seat of the New York State Legislature and the home of the Governor's office.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's initial architecture incorporated many Dutch influences, followed soon after by those of the English.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Quackenbush House, a Dutch Colonial brick mansion, was built c.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] 1736; Schuyler Mansion, a Georgian-style mansion, was built in 1765; and the oldest building in Albany is the 1728 Van Ostrande-Radliff House at 48 Hudson Avenue.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's housing varies greatly, with mostly row houses in the older sections of town, closer to the river.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Housing type quickly changes as one travels westward, beginning with two-family homes of the late 19th century, and one-family homes built after World War II in the western end of the city.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany City Hall, designed by Henry Hobson Richardson, was opened in 1883.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Capitol was opened in 1899 (after 32 years of construction) at a cost of $25 million, making it the most expensive government building at the time.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's Union Station, a major Beaux-Arts design, was under construction at the same time; it opened in 1900.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In 1912, the Beaux-Arts styled New York State Department of Education Building opened on Washington Avenue near the Capitol.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] It has a classical exterior, which features a block-long white marble colonnade.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The 1920s brought the Art Deco movement, which is illustrated by the Home Savings Bank Building (1927) on North Pearl Street and the Alfred E.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Smith Building (1930) on South Swan Street, two of Albany's tallest high-rises.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Architecture from the 1960s and 1970s is well represented in the city, especially at the W.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Averell Harriman State Office Building Campus (1950s and 1960s) and on the uptown campus of the University at Albany (1962–1971).
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The state office campus was planned in the 1950s by governor W.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Averell Harriman to offer more parking and easier access for state employees.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The uptown SUNY campus was built in the 1960s under Governor Rockefeller on the site of the city-owned Albany Country Club.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Straying from the popular open campus layout, SUNY Albany has a centralized building layout with administrative and classroom buildings at center surrounded by four student housing towers.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The design called for much use of concrete and glass, and the style has slender, round-topped columns and pillars reminiscent of those at Lincoln Center in New York City.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Downtown has seen a revival in recent decades, often considered to have begun with Norstar Bank's renovation of the former Union Station as its corporate headquarters in 1986.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Knickerbocker Arena (MVP Arena) was originally slated for suburban Colonie, but was instead built downtown and opened in 1990.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has teams in two top-level professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada (New York Atlas, and Albany Firebirds), and several minor-league sports teams with varying levels of support.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Devils were a minor league ice hockey team that moved to the city for the 2010–11 season.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] They played in the American Hockey League and were affiliated with the New Jersey Devils of the National Hockey League.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Devils replaced the Albany River Rats, who played in the Capital Region from 1990 to 2010, when they relocated to Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Devils moved to Binghamton, New York in 2017.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Times Union Center has previously hosted arena football teams including the Albany Firebirds in the Arena Football League (AFL) from 1990 to 2000 and then a team originally known as the Albany Conquest and later the Firebirds in the af2, the AFL's developmental league, from 2002 to 2009.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Empire played in the AFL from 2018 through the 2019 season when the league folded.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] A new Albany Empire was relaunched in the National Arena League for the 2021 season.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In 2023, Antonio Brown bought the team; after a series of problems with payments and personnel, the NAL suspended the franchise in the middle of the 2023 season.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] A relaunched Albany Firebirds franchise began playing in 2024.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Tri-City ValleyCats short season minor league baseball team have played at the Joseph L.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Bruno Stadium on the Hudson Valley Community College campus in North Greenbush since 2002.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Prior to the ValleyCats' arrival, the Albany-Colonie Diamond Dogs (1995–2002) played at Heritage Park in Colonie; due to financial pressures, and facing impending competition from the ValleyCats, the franchise folded in 2002.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Legends (International Basketball League), played in the Washington Avenue Armory from 2010 to 2014 before moving to Schenectady.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Patroons have played at the Armory on and off since 1982 and currently play in The Basketball League.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] With the large number of local colleges and universities around Albany, college sports are popular.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The University at Albany's Great Danes play at the Division I level in all sports.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The football team is a member of the Coastal Athletic Association while all other sports teams play as members of the America East Conference.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In 2006, UAlbany became the first SUNY-affiliated school to send a team to the NCAA Division I men's basketball tournament.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Siena Saints saw a rise in popularity after their men's basketball team made it to the NCAA Tournament in 2008, 2009, and 2010.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] All 18 Saints teams are Division I and play in the Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Although Siena's campus is in nearby Colonie, the men's basketball team plays at the Times Union Center.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] UAlbany hosted the New York Giants training camp from 1996 to 2012.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] On February 23, 2021, it was announced that the National Lacrosse League (NLL) would return to the city with the relocation of the New England Black Wolves.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The team was named the Albany FireWolves on April 15, 2021.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] This is the second NLL team to be based in the area; the first, the Albany Attack, played in the city from 2000 to 2003.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In 2023, the Premier Lacrosse League (PLL) selected cities for their 8 franchises, and Albany was chosen as the primary home for the New York Atlas.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In 2024, the Albany Firebirds began playing in the AFL at the MVP Arena.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] After one season in the AFL, the team moved to the AF1.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The 518 Ballers (American Basketball Association) have played at Our Savior's Christian School since 2023.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has more than 60 public parks and recreation areas.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park was organized as the Middle Public Square in 1806.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Its current location has been public property since the *Dongan Charter* of 1686 gave the city title to all property not privately owned.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park was designed by John Bogart and John Cuyler in 1870, and opened for public use the following year.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The original lake house, designed by Frederick W.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The park had previously been used as a cemetery; its graves were moved to Albany Rural Cemetery.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park is a popular place to exercise and play sports; skate during the winter; people-watch during Tulip Fest; and attend plays at the amphitheater during the summer.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Other parks in Albany include Lincoln Park, Buckingham Park, the Corning Preserve, the Albany Skyway and the Pine Bush.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Lincoln Park, southwest of the Empire State Plaza, was organized in 1886 and was originally known as Beaver Park.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Today, the park has a pool that is open during the summer months.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Buckingham Lake Park is between Manning Boulevard and Route 85 in the Buckingham Pond neighborhood; it contains a pond with fountains, a footpath, a playground, and picnic tables.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Riverfront Park at the Corning Preserve has an 800-seat amphitheatre that hosts events in non-winter months, most notably the *Alive at 5* summer concert series.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Preserve's visitors center details the ecology of the Hudson River and the local environment.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The park has a bike trail and boat launch and was effectively separated from downtown by Interstate 787 until the opening of the Hudson River Way in 2002.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Other public parks include Westland Hill Park, Hoffman Park, Beverwyck Park, and Liberty Park, today a small circular grassy patch in downtown on Hudson Avenue, which is Albany's oldest park.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Ridgefield Park is home to the clay courts of the Albany Tennis Club, one of the oldest tennis clubs in the United States.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The municipal golf course, New Course at Albany, was constructed in 1929 as the Albany Municipal Golf Course, later renamed the Capital Hills at Albany, and remodeled in 1991.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has a strong mayor-council government, which functions under the Dongan Charter, granted by colonial governor Thomas Dongan in 1686 when Albany was incorporated.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] A revised charter was adopted by referendum in 1998, but was legally reckoned as an amendment to the Dongan Charter.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] This gives Albany the distinction of having the oldest active city charter in the United States and "arguably the longest-running instrument of municipal government in the Western Hemisphere." The mayor, who is elected every four years, heads the executive branch of city government.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The current mayor, Kathy Sheehan, was first elected in 2013.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Common Council represents the legislative branch of city government and is made up of fifteen council members (each elected from one ward) and an at-large Common Council President.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The current president is Corey Ellis; he began his term in January 2018.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] While Albany has its own city government, it has also been the seat of Albany County since the county's formation in 1683 and the capital of New York since 1797.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] As such, the city is home to all branches of the county and state governments, as well as its own.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany City Hall sits on Eagle Street, opposite the State Capitol, and the Albany County Office Building is on State Street.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The state government has offices scattered throughout the city.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is in the 20th Congressional district, represented by Paul Tonko (D) in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The city is represented by Chuck Schumer (D) and Kirsten Gillibrand (D) in the United States Senate.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] On the state level, the city is in the 44th district in the New York Senate, represented by Patricia Fahy (D).
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In the New York Assembly, western Albany is in the 109th district, represented by Gabriella Romero (D) while downtown and eastern Albany are in the 108th district, represented by John T.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] As the seat of Albany County, the city is the location of the county's courts including Family Court, County Court, Surrogate Court, Supreme Court, and New York Court of Appeals.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is the site of a federal courthouse that houses the United States District Court for the Northern District of New York.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's politics have been dominated by the Democratic Party since the 1920s; Daniel (Uncle Dan) O'Connell established a political machine in the city with the election of William Stormont Hackett as mayor in 1922.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Prior to that, William Barnes Jr. had set up a Republican machine in the 1890s.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Barnes' success is attributed to the fact that he owned two newspapers in Albany and that he was the grandson of Thurlow Weed, the influential newspaper publisher and political boss.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] O'Connell's organization overcame Barnes' in 1922 and survived well into the 1980s (even after his death).
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In many instances, votes were outright bought.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Gerald Jennings' upset in the 1993 Democratic mayoral primary over Harold Joyce, who had the Democratic Party's formal endorsement and had only recently been its county chairman, is often cited as the end of the O'Connell era in Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In the early 21st century, Albany continued to be dominated by the Democratic Party.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Democratic Party enrollment in the city was 38,862 in 2009, while Republican enrollment was 3,487.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] As of 2022, every elected city position had been held by a Democrat since 1931.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In November 2013, Kathy Sheehan became the first woman to be elected Mayor of Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The City School District of Albany (CSDA) operates the city's public school system, which consists of 17 schools and learning centers; in addition, there are 7 charter schools, including Green Tech Charter High School, and Albany Leadership High School.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In the 2015–2016 school year, over 9,000 students were enrolled in the public school system.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The district had an average class size of 18, an 81-percent graduation rate, and a 5-percent dropout rate.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Although considered by the state to be one of the lowest-achieving high schools in New York, Albany High was listed as the nation's 976th best high school in a 2010 *Newsweek/Washington Post* report.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany also has a number of private schools, including the coed Bishop Maginn High School and Albany Free School; the all-boys Albany Academy; and the all-girls Academy of the Holy Names and Albany Academy for Girls.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Medical College (private), today part of Albany Medical Center, was founded in 1839.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany Law School (private) is the oldest law school in New York and the fourth-oldest in the country; it was opened in 1851.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] President William McKinley was an alumnus.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences (private) is the second-oldest pharmacy school in New York and the fifteenth-oldest in the United States.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Normal School, one of the oldest teachers colleges in the United States, opened in 1844; it was later known as the State Teachers College.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] It eventually evolved into the University at Albany, also known as SUNY Albany (public), which inherited the Normal School's original downtown campus on Western Avenue.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The center of the campus moved to its current Uptown Campus in the west end of the city in 1970.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] SUNY Albany is a unit of the State University of New York and one of only four university centers in the system.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Other colleges and universities in Albany include Empire State College, The College of Saint Rose, Excelsior College, Maria College, Mildred Elley, and Sage College of Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Nearby Hudson Valley Community College (HVCC) fills the community college niche in the Albany-Troy area.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The effect of the campuses on the city's population is substantial: Combining the student bodies of all the aforementioned campuses (except HVCC) results in 63,149 students, or almost 70 percent of the 2008 estimate of Albany's permanent population.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The *Times Union* is Albany's primary daily newspaper and the only one based close to the city; its headquarters moved from within city limits to suburban Colonie in the 1960s after a dispute with Mayor Corning over land needed for expansion.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Its circulation totals about 73,000 on weekdays and 143,000 on Sundays.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Serving Albany to a lesser degree are *The Daily Gazette*, based in Schenectady, and *The Record*, of Troy.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] *Metroland* is the alternative newsweekly in the area, publishing each Thursday, while *The Business Review* is a business weekly published each Friday.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The *Legislative Gazette*, another weekly newspaper, focuses exclusively on issues related to the Legislature and the state government.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] As of 2010, the Albany-Schenectady-Troy media market is the 63rd-largest in the country in terms of radio and the 57th-largest in terms of television audiences.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] It is a broadcast market with historical significance.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The pioneering influence of General Electric in Schenectady directly contributed to the area emerging as the birthplace of station-based television with WRGB; the station was also the first affiliate of NBC.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In 1947, the region was home to the first independently owned and operated commercial FM radio station in the United States: W47A.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] WGY was the second commercial radio station in New York and the twelfth in the nation.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Capital District is home to ABC affiliate WTEN 10, CBS affiliate WRGB 6 (also operating CW affiliate WCWN 45), Fox affiliate WXXA 23, NBC affiliate WNYT 13 (also operating MyNetworkTV affiliate WNYA 51), and PBS member station WMHT 17.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Charter Communications hosts Spectrum News Capital Region, the area's only local 24-hour news channel.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Thruway is the most prominent highway serving Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] From Albany westward, it is part of Interstate 90, connecting Albany with major cities such as Syracuse, Rochester and Buffalo.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] To the south, it becomes part of Interstate 87 and leads to New York City.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] A short un-tolled section of Interstate 90 extends around the northern and eastern portions of Albany before linking back up with the Berkshire extension of the Thruway, which leads to the Massachusetts Turnpike and ultimately to Boston.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] North of Albany, Interstate 87 follows the Northway to Canada at Champlain; Autoroute 15 continues into Quebec, linking Albany to Montreal.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Interstate 787 links downtown Albany to the southbound I-87/Thruway to the south, while to the north, it links with the free portion of Interstate 90 before continuing to Troy, Watervliet, Colonie, and Menands.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] By way of Route 7, I-787 connects to the Northway.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Since the closure of Union Station on Broadway, area passenger-rail service is provided by Amtrak at the Albany-Rensselaer station across the river in Rensselaer.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In 2009, the station saw more than 720,000 passengers, making it Amtrak's second-busiest in New York, behind Manhattan's Penn Station.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Amtrak provides service south to New York City; north to Montreal, and Burlington (Vermont); west to Niagara Falls, Toronto and Chicago; and east to Boston.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's major airport is Albany International Airport in Colonie.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Major airline service to Albany includes service by: American Airlines, Delta Air Lines, Southwest Airlines, JetBlue Airways, and United Airlines; Million Air is the local fixed-base operator.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] In 2010, Albany had the highest average airfare in New York, though the per-mile cost on its busiest routes was second-lowest in the state.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The Capital District Transportation Authority (CDTA) provides bus service throughout Albany and the surrounding area, including Schenectady, Troy, and Saratoga Springs.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The city was once served by an urban streetcar service maintained by the United Traction Company.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] As in many American cities, after the advent of the automobile, light rail services declined in Albany and were replaced by bus and taxi services.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Greyhound Lines, Trailways, Peter Pan, Short Line, Vermont Translines, and Yankee Trails buses all serve a downtown terminal.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Low-cost curbside bus service from the SUNY Albany campus and the Rensselaer station is also provided by Megabus, with direct service to New York City.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Albany, long an important Hudson River port, today serves domestic and international ships and barges through the Port of Albany-Rensselaer, on both sides of the river.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The port has the largest mobile harbor crane in the state of New York.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Barge Canal, the ultimate successor of the Erie Canal, is in use today, largely by tourist and private boats.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] The city of Nijmegen, Netherlands connected with Albany following World War II.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] With the help of the Catholic university in Albany, the Catholic University of Nijmegen (Radboud University Nijmegen) rebuilt its partly destroyed library, with over 50,000 books being donated to the Dutch university.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] To show its gratitude for post-war assistance, the city sent Albany 50,000 tulip bulbs in 1948; this act led to the establishment of the annual Tulip Festival.
[src:technical-alliance/albany-new-york-p02] Most of the other connections were made in the 1980s during Mayor Whalen's term in office as part of his cultural expansion program.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] Born in Lowell, Massachusetts, the daughter of Charles Dana Barrows and Marion Merrill, Alice graduated from Vassar College with an A.B.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] During 1901–03, she was employed as an English teacher at the Packer Collegiate Institute, then she taught English at the Ethical School in New York City from 1903–04.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] She became an English teacher at her alma mater until 1908 and was a graduate fellow of Columbia University.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] In 1909, Alice became a social investigator for the Russell Sage Foundation, mentored by Mary van Kleeck, who was later director of the Department of Industrial Studies.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] Together they completed a report of women in the millinery industry.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] Two years later in 1911, she was named director of the Vocational Education Survey.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] She was described as a "specialist in school buildings" in a 1928 profile.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] In 1934, a Congressional Investigation was held to examine statements Dr.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] Wirt made regarding a meeting in Alice Barrows' home a year earlier.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] The "Wirt Incident" was widely reported and provoked much controversy.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] Barrows and several other government employees revealed to Wirt they were members of the Communist party.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] A June 1945 Venona project decryption of the Washington, D.C.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] KGB Office to Moscow's Eighth Department, the political intelligence wing, relayed information on matters regarding President Truman and Attorney General Francis Biddle.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] KGB agent Charles Kramer, who served on the staff of several Senate Subcommittees, and Barrows are the sources of the information.
[src:technical-alliance/alice-barrows] The organization Barrows served as Director was found in 1953 to be a Communist front organization by the Subversive Activities Control Board (SACB).
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] The **American Statistical Association** (**ASA**) is the main professional organization for statisticians and related professionals in the United States.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] It was founded in Boston, Massachusetts, on November 27, 1839, and is the second-oldest continuously operating professional society in the U.S. behind the Massachusetts Medical Society (founded in 1781).
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] ASA services statisticians, quantitative scientists, and users of statistics across many academic areas and applications.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] The association publishes a variety of journals and sponsors several international conferences every year.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] As of 2022, the ASA membership exceeds 19,000 professionals found in government, academia, and the private sector.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] Organizational members and corporate supporters of the ASA include AstraZeneca, Merck & Co., the National Security Agency, Pfizer, RTI International, StataCorp and Westat.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] In November 2018, ASA Board of Directors approved a code of conduct statement on Justice, Equity, Diversity, and Inclusion (JEDI).
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] It was reviewed and updated by ASA BOD in 2019, 2021, and most recently in 2023.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] Fisher Award and Lectureship was changed to COPSS Distinguished Achievement Award and Lectureship.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] The change follows discussions about Fisher's views on race and eugenics.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] In 2021, ASA established the Justice, Equity, Diversity, and Inclusion Outreach Group, known as the JEDI Outreach Group.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] New Fellowships of the ASA are granted annually by the ASA Committee on Fellows.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] Candidates must have been members for the preceding three years but may be nominated by anyone.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] The maximum number of recipients each year is one-third of one percent of the ASA membership.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] ASA is organized in Sections, Chapters and Committees.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] Chapters are arranged geographically, representing 78 areas across the US and Canada.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] An example of an early and large chapter is the SoCalASA.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] Sections are subject-area and industry-area interest groups covering 22 sub-disciplines.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] ASA has more than 60 committees coordinating meetings, publications, education, careers, and special-interest topics involving statisticians.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] ASA is a member society of the Conference Board of the Mathematical Sciences.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] To apply for continuing accreditation, PStat members are expected to complete 60 hours of professional development activities each year.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] The ASA also offers the Graduate Statistician status (GStat) as of April 2014.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] It serves as a preparatory accreditation suitable for graduate students.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] A list of PStat and GStat accredited members is available on the ASA website.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] The monthly magazine for members *Amstat News* is available online and features first-person statistician stories called My ASA Story.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] Based on the monthly column in *AmStat News,* the ASA produces a website called STAT*tr@k* with new articles every month for early career statisticians and data analysts, recent graduates, or those who are in a statistics program.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] Quarterly magazine *Chance* and bimonthly magazine Significance are geared toward a general audience.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] Meetings provide a platform for scholars and practitioners to exchange research, job opportunities and ideas with each other.
[src:technical-alliance/american-statistical-association] ASA holds an annual meeting called Joint Statistical Meetings (JSM), a conference on statistical methodologies and applications called Spring Research Conference (SRC), Conference on Statistical Practice (CSP), and sponsors multiple international meetings and special-interest group meetings.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] MacKaye helped pioneer the idea of land preservation for recreation and conservation purposes and was a strong advocate of balancing human needs and those of nature; he coined the term "geotechnics" to describe this philosophy.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] In addition to writing the first argument against urban sprawl, MacKaye also authored two books, *The New Exploration: A Philosophy of Regional Planning* and *Expedition Nine: A Return to a Region*.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] Thirteen of his essays were published in the collection *From Geography to Geotechnics*.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] Emile Benton MacKaye was born in Stamford, Connecticut, on March 6, 1879, to actor and dramatist Steele MacKaye and his wife Mary.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] He was the sixth of seven children (and last son) born to the couple.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] Benton's name was derived from his paternal grandmother, Emily Benton Steele.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] They lived in farms and houses in Brattleboro, Vermont; Norton, Massachusetts; Mount Vernon, New York; and Ridgefield, Connecticut, before moving to New York City in 1885.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] In order to escape the bustle of city life, the family took to visiting Shirley Center, Massachusetts, a quiet village 30 miles from Boston that Benton would continue to visit throughout his life.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] In 1888, his brother William purchased an estate in Shirley that the family would come to call "The Cottage".
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] Eight-year-old Benton was enamored with the beauty and freedom of the country, proclaiming he enjoyed it far more than urban existence.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] Shortly after William died of a sudden respiratory disease in 1889, the family moved to Washington, D.C.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] An indifferent student, MacKaye once described school as "a place that boys like to run away from".
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] Drawn to the study of the natural world, he often pursued knowledge on his own; he spent much time in the Smithsonian, making sketches of the abundant collections and volunteering to help scientists in their labs.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] He befriended assistant curator James Benedict and attended lectures given by Civil War hero John Wesley Powell and arctic explorer Robert Peary.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] His early immersion in nature helped him cope with tragedy that eventually struck the MacKaye family; his frequently absent father died in 1894, when Benton was fourteen.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] While attending high school in Cambridge, he began charting the landscape around Shirley Center, documenting vegetation, landforms, rivers, and roads in numbered notebooks.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] After dropping out of school in order to prepare for college entrance exams on his own, in 1896 MacKaye followed his brothers—James, an engineer and philosopher, and Percy, a dramatist and poet—to Harvard University, where he studied geology.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] It took him two years to overcome deficiencies in subjects such as German, algebra and physics.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] When he graduated with a Bachelor of Arts in 1905, MacKaye was still unsure what career he should embark upon.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] During this time, he read Thomas Henry Huxley's 1877 work *Physiography: An Introduction to the Study of Nature*—a gift from his brother James and a work that would prove influential in MacKaye's future regional planning.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] In 1903 he enrolled in Harvard's newly established forestry school; he was the school's first student to graduate in 1905.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] For the next five years, he alternated between teaching at Harvard's forestry school near Petersham, Massachusetts, and working as a forest assistant with the United States Forest Service.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] MacKaye made some important contributions during the early years of national forestry.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] While working as a forest examiner in the 1910s, he performed groundbreaking research on the impacts of forest cover on surface runoff in New Hampshire's White Mountains.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] This was during a time in which an intense debate regarding the connection between deforestation and irregular streamflow was occurring, and MacKaye's scientific evidence that forest cover controlled streamflow helped in the creation of the White Mountain National Forest.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] In 1913, while living in Washington D.C., Mackaye helped form a social activist group called the Hell Raisers.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] Composed of government workers, congressional staffers, and journalists, the informal group aimed to raise public awareness about social and political issues.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] He married the suffragist Jessie Belle Hardy Stubbs in 1915.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] MacKaye's article "An Appalachian Trail: A Project in Regional Planning," which proposed the construction of the Appalachian Trail, was published in the October 1921 issue of *Journal of the American Institute of Architects*.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] The article was partly inspired by the Green Mountain Club which had helped usher in Vermont's Long Trail.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] The article triggered sixteen years of effort, organized through hundreds of local trail associations and community groups, to blaze and build a 2,192-mile trail along the crests of the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] MacKaye hoped to spark a "back to the land" movement to relieve the ills of urban industrial life.
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] In his 2002 book *Long Trails of the Southeast*, writer and avid hiker Johnny Molloy wrote that the Benton MacKaye Trail "is what I imagine the Appalachian Trail was like many decades ago—a lesser tamed path, steep in places, rough in spots, and still evolving".
[src:technical-alliance/benton-mackaye] On June 17, 2011 he was inducted into the Appalachian Trail Hall of Fame at the Appalachian Trail Museum as a charter member.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is home to the oldest campus in the University of California, the University of California, Berkeley, and the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, which is managed and operated by the university.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] It also has the Graduate Theological Union, one of the largest religious studies institutions in the world.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is considered one of the most socially progressive cities in the United States.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The site of today's City of Berkeley was the territory of the Chochenyo/Huchiun Ohlone people when the first Europeans arrived.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Human remains and skeletons from Native American burials have been unearthed in West Berkeley and on campus alongside Strawberry Creek.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Other artifacts were discovered in the 1950s in the downtown area during remodeling of a commercial building, near the upper course of the creek.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The first people of European descent (most of whom were of mixed race and born in America) arrived with the De Anza Expedition in 1776.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The De Anza Expedition led to establishment of the Spanish Presidio of San Francisco at the entrance to San Francisco Bay (the "Golden Gate)." Luis Peralta was among the soldiers at the Presidio.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] For his services to the King of Spain, he was granted a vast stretch of land on the east shore of San Francisco Bay (the *contra costa*, "opposite shore") for a ranch, including that portion that now comprises the City of Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Luis Peralta named his holding "Rancho San Antonio." The primary activity of the ranch was raising cattle for meat and hides, but hunting and farming were also pursued.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Eventually, Peralta gave portions of the ranch to each of his four sons.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] What is now Berkeley lies mostly in the portion that went to Peralta's son Domingo, with a little in the portion that went to another son, Vicente.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] No artifact survives of the Domingo or Vicente ranches, but their names survive in Berkeley street names (Vicente, Domingo, and Peralta).
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] However, legal title to all land in the City of Berkeley remains based on the original Peralta land grant.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The Peraltas' Rancho San Antonio continued after Alta California passed from Spanish to Mexican sovereignty following the Mexican War of Independence.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] However, the advent of U.S. sovereignty after the Mexican–American War, and especially, the gold rush, saw the Peraltas' lands quickly encroached on by squatters and diminished by dubious legal proceedings.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The lands of the brothers Domingo and Vicente were quickly reduced to reservations close to their respective ranch homes.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The rest of the land was surveyed and parceled out to various American claimants (*See* Kellersberger's Map).
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Politically, the area that became Berkeley was initially part of a vast Contra Costa County.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] On March 25, 1853, Alameda County was created from a partition of Contra Costa County, as well as from a small portion of Santa Clara County.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The area that became Berkeley was then the northern part of the "Oakland Township" subdivision of Alameda County.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] During this period, "Berkeley" was mostly a mix of open land, farms, and ranches, with a small, though busy, wharf by the bay.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 1866, Oakland's private College of California looked for a new site.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] It settled on a location north of Oakland along the foot of the Contra Costa Range (later called the Berkeley Hills) on Strawberry Creek, at an elevation of about 500 feet (150 m) above the bay, commanding a view of the Bay Area and the Pacific Ocean through the Golden Gate.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] According to the *Centennial Record of the University of California*, "In 1866, at Founders' Rock, a group of College of California men watched two ships standing out to sea through the Golden Gate.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The College of California's College Homestead Association planned to raise funds for the new campus by selling off adjacent parcels of land.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] To this end, they laid out a plat and street grid that became the basis of Berkeley's modern street plan.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Their plans fell far short of their desires, and they began a collaboration with the State of California that culminated in 1868 with the creation of the public University of California.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] As construction began on the new site, more residences were constructed in the vicinity of the new campus.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] At the same time, a settlement of residences, saloons, and various industries grew around the wharf area called Ocean View.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] A horsecar ran from Temescal in Oakland to the university campus along what is now Telegraph Avenue.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] By the 1870s, the transcontinental railroad reached its terminus in Oakland.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 1876, a branch line of the Central Pacific Railroad, the Berkeley Branch Railroad, was laid from a junction with the mainline called Shellmound (now a part of Emeryville) into what is now downtown Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] That same year, the mainline of the transcontinental railroad into Oakland was re-routed, putting the right-of-way along the bay shore through Ocean View.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] There was a strong prohibition movement in Berkeley at this time.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 1876, the state enacted the "mile limit law", which forbade sale or public consumption of alcohol within one mile (1.6 km) of the new University of California.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Then, in 1899, Berkeley residents voted to make their city an alcohol-free zone.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Scientists, scholars and religious leaders spoke vehemently of the dangers of alcohol.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] On April 1, 1878, the people of Ocean View and the area around the university campus, together with local farmers, were granted incorporation by the State of California as the Town of Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The first elected trustees of the town were the slate of Denis Kearney's anti-Chinese Workingman's Party, who were particularly favored in the working-class area of the former Ocean View, now called West Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] During the 1880s Berkeley had segregated housing and anti-Chinese laws.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The area near the university became known for a time as East Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Due to the influence of the university, the modern age came quickly to Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Electric lights and the telephone were in use by 1888.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Electric streetcars soon replaced the horsecar.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] A silent film of one of these early streetcars in Berkeley can be seen at the Library of Congress website.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley's slow growth ended abruptly with the Great San Francisco earthquake of 1906.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The town and other parts of the East Bay escaped serious damage, and thousands of refugees flowed across the Bay.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Among them were most of San Francisco's painters and sculptors, who between 1907 and 1911 created one of the largest art colonies west of Chicago.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Cannon described the founding of the Berkeley Art Association and the rivalries of competing studios and art clubs.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 1908, a statewide referendum that proposed moving the California state capital to Berkeley was defeated by a margin of about 33,000 votes.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The city had named streets around the proposed capitol grounds for California counties.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] They bear those names today, a legacy of the failed referendum.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] On March 4, 1909, following public referendums, the citizens of Berkeley were granted a new charter by the State of California, and the Town of Berkeley became the City of Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Rapid growth continued up to the crash of 1929.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The Great Depression hit Berkeley hard, but not as hard as many other places in the U.S., thanks in part to the university.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 1916, Berkeley implemented single-family zoning as an effort to keep minorities out of white neighborhoods.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] This has been described as the first implementation of single-family zoning in the United States.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] By 2021, nearly half of Berkeley's residential neighborhoods were still exclusively zoned for single-family homes.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 2025, Berkeley legalized small multi-family buildings in most of the city.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] On September 17, 1923, a major fire swept down the hills toward the university campus and the downtown section.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Around 640 structures burned before a late-afternoon sea breeze stopped its progress, allowing firefighters to put it out.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The next big growth occurred with the advent of World War II, when large numbers of people moved to the Bay Area to work in the many war industries, such as the immense Kaiser Shipyards in nearby Richmond.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] One who moved out, but played a big role in the outcome of the war, was U.C. professor and Berkeley resident J.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] During the war, an Army base, Camp Ashby, was temporarily sited in Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The element berkelium was synthesized utilizing the 60-inch (1.5 m) cyclotron at UC Berkeley, and named in 1949, in recognition of the university, thus placing the city's name in the list of elements.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] During the 1940s, many African Americans migrated to Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 1950, the Census Bureau reported Berkeley's population as 11.7% black and 84.6% white.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The postwar years brought moderate growth to the city, as events on the U.C. campus began to build up to the recognizable activism of the sixties.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In the 1950s, McCarthyism induced the university to demand a loyalty oath from its professors, many of whom refused to sign the oath on the principle of freedom of thought.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] House committee (HUAC) came to San Francisco to investigate the influence of communists in the Bay Area.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Their presence was met by protesters, including many from the university.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Meanwhile, a number of U.C. students became active in the civil rights movement.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Finally, in 1964, the university provoked a massive student protest by banning distribution of political literature on campus.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] This protest became the Free Speech Movement.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] As the Vietnam War rapidly escalated in the ensuing years, so did student activism at the university, particularly that organized by the Vietnam Day Committee.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is strongly identified with the rapid social changes, civic unrest, and political upheaval that characterized the mid-to-late 1960s.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In that period, Berkeley—especially Telegraph Avenue—became a focal point for the hippie movement, which spilled over the Bay from San Francisco.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Many hippies were apolitical drop-outs, rather than students, but in the heady atmosphere of Berkeley in 1967–1969 there was considerable overlap between the hippie movement and the radical left.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] An iconic event in the Berkeley Sixties scene was a conflict over a parcel of university property south of the contiguous campus site that came to be called "People's Park".
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The battle over the disposition of People's Park resulted in a month-long occupation of Berkeley by the National Guard on orders of then-Governor Ronald Reagan.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In the end, the park remained undeveloped, and remained so for decades.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] A spin-off, *People's Park Annex*, was established at the same time by activist citizens of Berkeley on a strip of land above the Bay Area Rapid Transit ("BART") underground construction along Hearst Avenue northwest of the U.C. campus.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The land had also been intended for development, but was turned over to the city by BART and is now Ohlone Park.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The era of large public protest in Berkeley waned considerably with the end of the Vietnam War in 1975.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] While the 1960s were the heyday of liberal activism in Berkeley, it remains one of the most overwhelmingly Democratic cities in the United States.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] After the 1960s, Berkeley banned most new housing construction, in particular apartments.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Increasing enrollment at the university led to replacement of older buildings by large apartment buildings, especially in older parts of the city near the university and downtown.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Increasing enrollment also led the university to wanting to redevelop certain places of Berkeley, especially Southside, but more specifically People's Park.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Preservationists passed the Neighborhood Protection Ordinance in 1973 by ballot measure and the Landmarks Preservation Ordinance in 1974 by the City Council.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Together, these ordinances brought most new construction to a halt.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Facing rising housing costs, residents voted to enact rent control and vacancy control in 1980.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] For cities such as Berkeley, where rent control was already in place, the law limited the use of rent control to units built before the local rent-control law was enacted, i.e.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] During the 1970s and 1980s, activists increased their power in local government.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] This era also saw major developments in Berkeley's environmental and food culture.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley's last Republican mayor, Wallace J.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Alice Waters opened Chez Panisse in 1971.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The first curbside recycling program in the U.S. was started by the Ecology Center in 1973.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] As the city leaned more and more Democratic, local politics became divided between "Progressives" and "Moderates".
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] 1984 saw the Progressives take the majority for the first time.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Nancy Skinner became the first UC Berkeley student elected to City Council.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 1986, in reaction to the 1984 election, a ballot measure switched Berkeley from at-large to district-based elections for city council.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 1983, Berkeley's Domestic Partner Task Force was established, which in 1984 made policy recommendation to the school board, which passed domestic partner legislation.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The legislation became a model for similar measures nationwide.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 1995, California's Costa–Hawkins Act ended vacancy control, allowing rents to increase when a tenant moved out.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Despite a slow down in 2005–2007, median home prices and rents remain dramatically higher than the rest of the nation, fueled by spillover from the San Francisco housing shortage and population growth.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] South and West Berkeley underwent gentrification, with some historically Black neighborhoods such as the Adeline Corridor seeing a 50% decline in Black / African American population from 1990 to 2010.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In the 1990s, public television's Frontline documentary series featured race relations at Berkeley's only public high school, Berkeley High School.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] With an economy dominated by the University of California and a high-demand housing market, Berkeley was relatively unaffected by the Great Recession.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] State budget cuts caused the university to increase the number of out-of-state and international students, with international enrollment, mostly from Asia, rising from 2,785 in 2007 to 5,951 in 2016.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Since then, more international restaurants have opened downtown and on Telegraph Avenue, including East Asian chains such as Ippudo and Daiso.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] A wave of downtown apartment construction began in 1998.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 2006, the Berkeley Oak Grove Protest began protesting construction of a new sports center annex to Memorial Stadium at the expense of a grove of oak trees on the UC campus.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The protest ended in September 2008 after a lengthy court process.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 2007–2008, Berkeley received media attention due to demonstrations against a Marine Corps recruiting office in downtown Berkeley and a series of controversial motions by Berkeley's city council regarding opposition to Marine recruiting.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] During the fall of 2010, the Berkeley Student Food Collective opened after many protests on the UC Berkeley campus due to the proposed opening of the fast food chain Panda Express.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Students and community members worked together to open a collectively run grocery store right off of the UC Berkeley campus, where the community can buy local, seasonal, humane, and organic foods.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The Berkeley Student Food Collective still operates at 2440 Bancroft Way.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] On September 18, 2012, Berkeley became what may be the first city in the U.S. to officially proclaim a day recognizing bisexuals: September 23, which is known as Celebrate Bisexuality Day.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] On September 2, 2014, the city council approved a measure to provide free medical marijuana to low-income patients.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The Measure D soda tax was approved by Berkeley voters on November 4, 2014, the first such tax in the United States.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In the fall of 2011, the nationwide Occupy Wall Street movement came to two Berkeley locations: on the campus of the University of California and as an encampment in Civic Center Park.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] During a Black Lives Matter protest on December 6, 2014, police use of tear gas and batons to clear protesters from Telegraph Avenue led to a riot and five consecutive days and nights of protests, marches, and freeway occupations in Berkeley and Oakland.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Afterwards, changes were implemented by the Police Department to avoid escalation of violence and to protect bystanders during protests.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] During a protest against bigotry and U.S.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] President Donald Trump in August 2017, self-described anti-fascist protesters attacked Trump supporters in attendance.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Sometimes called "antifa", these ‘anti-fascist’ activists were clad in black shirts and other black attire, while some carried shields and others had masks or bandanas hiding their faces to help them evade capture after street fighting.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] These protests spanned February to September 2017 (See more at 2017 Berkeley Protests).
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 2019, protesters took up residence in People's Park against tree-chopping and were arrested by police in riot gear.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Many activists saw this as the university preparing to develop the park.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The city of Berkeley has historically been a central location for homeless communities in the Bay Area.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The city has passed ordinances to oust homeless individuals from Berkeley on multiple occasions.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Despite efforts to improve social services and remove unhoused individuals from the streets, homelessness has continued to be a significant problem in Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] A culture of anti-establishment and sociopolitical activism marked the 1960s.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The San Francisco Bay Area became a hotspot for hippie counterculture, and Berkeley became a haven for nonconformists and anarchists from all over the United States.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Most public discourse around homelessness in Berkeley at this time was centered around the idea of street-living as an expression of counterculture.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Many non-student youth and adolescents sought alternative lifestyles and opted for voluntary homelessness during this time.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 1969, People's Park was created and eventually became a haven for "small-time drug dealers, street people, and the homeless".
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Although the City of Berkeley has moved unhoused individuals from its streets, sometimes even relocating them to an unused landfill, People's Park has remained a safe space for them since its inception.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The park has become one of the few relatively safe spaces for homeless individuals to congregate in Berkeley and the greater Bay Area.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Stereotypes of homeless people as deviant individuals who chose to live vagrant lifestyles continued to color the discourse around street-dwellers in American cities.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] However, this time period was also characterized by a subtle shift in the perception of unhoused individuals.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The public began to realize that homelessness affected not only single men, but also women, children, and entire families.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] This recognition set the stage for the City of Berkeley's attitude towards homelessness in the next decade.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Organizations such as Building Opportunities for Self Sufficiency (BOSS) were established in 1971 in response to the needs of individuals with mental illness being released to the streets by state hospital closures.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In the 1990s, the City of Berkeley faced a substantial increase in the need for emergency housing shelters and saw a rise in the average amount of time individuals spent without stable housing.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] As housing became a more widespread problem, the general public, Berkeley City Council, and the University of California became increasingly anti-homeless in their opinions.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 1994, Berkeley City Council considered the implementation of a set of anti-homeless laws that the *San Francisco Chronicle* described as being "among the strictest in the country".
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] These laws prohibited sitting, sleeping and begging in public spaces, and outlawed panhandling from people in a variety of contexts, such as sitting on public benches, buying a newspaper from a rack, or waiting in line for a movie.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In February 1995, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) sued the city for infringing free speech rights through its proposed anti-panhandling law.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The following month, the Street Spirit, a monthly newspaper written for and by people experiencing homelessness, published its first of hundreds of issues covering homelessness in the Bay Area and across the nation.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In May of that same year, a federal judge ruled that the anti-panhandling law did violate the First Amendment, but left the anti-sitting and sleeping laws untouched.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Following the implementation of these anti-sitting and sleeping ordinances in 1998, Berkeley increased its policing of homeless adults and youth, particularly in the shopping district surrounding Telegraph Avenue.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The mayor at that time, Shirley Dean, proposed a plan to increase both social support services for homeless youth and enforcement of anti-encampment laws.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Unhoused youth countered this plan with a request for the establishment of the city's first youth shelter, more trash cans, and more frequent cleaning of public bathrooms.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The City of Berkeley's 2017 annual homeless report and point-in-time count (PIT) estimate that on a given night, 972 people are homeless.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Sixty-eight percent (664 people) of these individuals are also unsheltered, living in places not considered suitable for human habitation, such as cars or streets.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Long-term homelessness in Berkeley is double the national average, with 27% of the city's homeless population facing chronic homelessness.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Chronic homelessness has been on the rise since 2015, and has been largely a consequence of the constrained local housing market.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 2015, rent in Alameda County increased by 25%, while the average household income only grew by 5%.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The City of Berkeley's 2017 report also estimated the number of unaccompanied youth in Berkeley at 189 individuals, 19% of the total homeless population in the city.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Homeless youth display greater risk of mental health issues, behavioral problems, and substance abuse, than any other homeless age group.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Furthermore, homeless youth identifying as LGBTQ+ are exposed to greater rates of physical and sexual abuse, and higher risk for sexually transmitted diseases, predominantly HIV.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The City of Berkeley has seen a consistent rise in the number of chronically homeless individuals over the past 30 years, and has implemented a number of different projects to reduce the number of people living on the streets.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 2008, the City focused its efforts on addressing chronic homelessness.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] This led to a 48% decline in the number of chronically homeless individuals reported in the 2009 Berkeley PIT.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] However, the number of "hidden homeless" individuals (those coping with housing insecurity by staying at a friend or relative's residence), increased significantly, likely in response to rising housing costs and costs of living.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 2012, the City considered measures that banned sitting in commercial areas throughout Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The measure was met with strong public opposition and did not pass.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] However, the City saw a strong need for it to implement rules addressing encampments and public usage of space as well as assessing the resources needed to assist the unhoused population.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In response to these needs the City of Berkeley established the Homeless Task Force, headed by then-Councilmember Jesse Arreguín.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Since its formation, the Task Force has proposed a number of different recommendations, from expanding the City Homeless Outreach and Mobile Crisis Teams, to building a short-term transitional shelter for unhoused individuals.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city's 17.7-square-mile (46 km2) area includes 10.5 square miles (27 km2) of land and 7.2 square miles (19 km2) (40.83%) water, most of it part of San Francisco Bay.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley borders the cities of Albany, Oakland, and Emeryville and Contra Costa County, including unincorporated Kensington, as well as San Francisco Bay.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley lies within telephone area code 510 (until September 2, 1991, Berkeley was part of the 415 telephone code that now covers only San Francisco and Marin counties), and the postal ZIP codes are 94701 through 94710, 94712, and 94720 for the University of California campus.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Most of Berkeley lies on a rolling sedimentary plain that rises gently from sea level to the base of the Berkeley Hills.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] East of the Hayward Fault along the base of the hills, elevation increases more rapidly.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The highest peak along the ridge line above Berkeley is Grizzly Peak, at an elevation of 1,754 feet (535 m).
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] A number of small creeks run from the hills to the Bay through Berkeley: Codornices, Schoolhouse, and Strawberry Creeks are the principal streams.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Most of these are largely culverted once they reach the plain west of the hills.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The Berkeley Hills are part of the Pacific Coast Ranges, and run in a northwest–southeast alignment.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Exposed in the Berkeley Hills are cherts and shales of the Claremont Formation (equivalent to the Monterey Formation), conglomerate and sandstone of the Orinda Formation and lava flows of the Moraga Volcanics.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Of similar age to the Moraga Volcanics (extinct), within the Northbrae neighborhood of Berkeley, are outcroppings of erosion resistant rhyolite.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] These rhyolite formations can be seen in several city parks and in the yards of a number of private residences.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Indian Rock Park in the northeastern part of Berkeley near the Arlington/Marin Circle features a large example.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is traversed by the Hayward Fault Zone, a major branch of the San Andreas Fault to the west.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] No large earthquake has occurred on the Hayward Fault near Berkeley in historic times (except possibly in 1836), but seismologists warn about the geologic record of large temblors several times in the deeper past.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The current assessment is that a Bay Area earthquake of magnitude 6.7 or greater within the next 30 years is likely, with the Hayward Fault having the highest likelihood among faults in the Bay Area of being the epicenter.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Moreover, like much of the Bay Area, Berkeley has many areas of some risk to soil liquefaction, with the flat areas closer to the shore at low to high susceptibility.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The 1868 Hayward earthquake did occur on the southern segment of the Hayward Fault in the vicinity of today's city of Hayward.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] This quake destroyed the county seat of Alameda County then located in San Leandro, and it subsequently moved to Oakland.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] It was strongly felt in San Francisco, causing major damage.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] It was regarded as the "Great San Francisco earthquake" prior to 1906.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] It produced a furrow in the ground along the fault line in Berkeley, across the grounds of the new State Asylum for the Deaf, Dumb and Blind then under construction, which was noted by one early University of California professor.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Although no significant damage was reported to most of the few Berkeley buildings of the time, the 1868 quake did destroy the vulnerable adobe home of Domingo Peralta in north Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Today, evidence of the Hayward Fault's "creeping" is visible at various locations in Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Cracked roadways, sharp jogs in streams, and springs mark the fault's path.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] However, since it cuts across the base of the hills, the creep is often concealed by or confused with slide activity.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Some of the slide activity itself, however, results from movement on the Hayward Fault.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] A notorious segment of the Hayward Fault runs lengthwise down the middle of Memorial Stadium at the mouth of Strawberry Canyon on the University of California campus.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Photos and measurements show the movement of the fault through the stadium.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has a warm-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csb* in the Köppen climate classification), with warm, dry summers and cool, wet winters.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley's location directly opposite the Golden Gate ensures that typical eastward fog flow blankets the city more often than its neighbors.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The summers are cooler than a typical Mediterranean climate thanks to upwelling ocean currents along the California coast.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] These help produce cool and foggy nights and mornings.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Winter is punctuated with rainstorms of varying ferocity and duration, but also produces stretches of bright sunny days and clear cold nights.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] It does not normally snow, though occasionally the hilltops get a dusting.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Spring and fall are transitional and intermediate, with some rainfall and variable temperature.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Summer typically brings night and morning low clouds or fog, followed by sunny, warm days.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The warmest and driest months are typically June through September, with the highest temperatures occurring in September.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Mid-summer (July–August) is often a bit cooler due to the sea breezes and fog common then.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In a year, there are an average of 2.9 days with highs of 90 °F (32 °C) or higher, and an average of 0.8 days with lows of 32 °F (0 °C) or lower.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The highest recorded temperature was 107 °F (42 °C) on June 15, 2000, and July 16, 1993, and the lowest recorded temperature was 24 °F (−4 °C) on December 22, 1990.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] February is normally the wettest month, averaging 5.21 inches (132 mm) of precipitation.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Average annual precipitation is 25.40 inches (645 mm), falling on an average of 63.7 days each year.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The most rainfall in one month was 14.49 inches (368 mm) in February 1998.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The most rainfall in 24 hours was 6.98 inches (177 mm) on January 4, 1982.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] As in most of California, the heaviest rainfall years are usually associated with warm water El Niño episodes in the Pacific (e.g., 1982–83; 1997–98), which bring in drenching "Pineapple Express" storms.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In contrast, dry years are often associated with cold Pacific La Niña episodes.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Light snow has fallen on rare occasions.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Snow has generally fallen every several years on the higher peaks of the Berkeley Hills.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In the late spring and early fall, strong offshore winds of sinking air typically develop, bringing heat and dryness to the area.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In the spring, this is not usually a problem as vegetation is still moist from winter rains, but extreme dryness prevails by the fall, creating a danger of wildfires.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In September 1923, a major fire swept through the neighborhoods north of the university campus, stopping just short of downtown.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] On October 20, 1991, gusty, hot winds fanned a conflagration along the Berkeley–Oakland border, killing 25 people and injuring 150, as well as destroying 2,449 single-family dwellings and 437 apartment and condominium units.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The 2020 United States census reported that Berkeley had a population of 124,321.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The population density was 11,874 people per square mile of land area (4,584/km2).
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] There were 17,018 (13.7%) of Hispanic or Latino ancestry, of any race.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] According to the 2022 American Community Survey estimate, the median income for a household was $104,716 and the median income for a family was $177,068.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Males had a median income of $102,565 versus $82,772 for females.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The per capita income for the city was $63,310.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] About 4.3% of families and 17.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 6% of those under age 18 and 8.1% of those age 65 or over.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] There were 12,209 people (10.8%) of Hispanic or Latino ancestry, of any race.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] 6.8% of the city's population was of Mexican ancestry.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The Census reported that 99,731 people (88.6% of the population) lived in households, 12,430 (11.0%) lived in non-institutionalized group quarters, and 419 (0.4%) were institutionalized.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] There were 46,029 households, out of which 8,467 (18.4%) had children under the age of 18 living in them, 13,569 (29.5%) were opposite-sex married couples living together, 3,855 (8.4%) had a female householder with no husband present, 1,368 (3.0%) had a male householder with no wife present.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] There were 2,931 (6.4%) unmarried opposite-sex partnerships, and 961 (2.1%) same-sex married couples or partnerships.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] 16,904 households (36.7%) were made up of individuals, and 4,578 (9.9%) had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] There were 18,792 families (40.8% of all households); the average family size was 2.81.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.0%; the rental vacancy rate was 4.5%.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] 45,096 people (40.1% of the population) lived in owner-occupied housing units and 54,635 people (48.5%) lived in rental housing units.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] For every 100 females, there were 95.6 males.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.2 males.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] According to the 2011 American Community Survey 5-Year estimate, the median income for a household in the city was $60,908, and the median income for a family was $102,976.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Males had a median income of $67,476 versus $57,319 for females.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The per capita income for the city was $38,896.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] About 7.2% of families and 18.3% of the population were below the poverty line, including 13.2% of those under age 18 and 9.2% of those age 65 or over.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has a higher-than-average crime rate, particularly property crime, though the crime rate has fallen significantly since 2000.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is served by Amtrak (Capitol Corridor), AC Transit, BART (Ashby, Downtown Berkeley Station and North Berkeley) and bus shuttles operated by major employers including UC Berkeley and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The Eastshore Freeway (Interstate 80 and Interstate 580) runs along the bay shoreline.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Each day there is an influx of thousands of cars into the city by commuting UC faculty, staff and students, making parking for more than a few hours an expensive proposition.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has one of the highest rates of bicycle and pedestrian commuting in the nation.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is the safest city of its size in California for pedestrians and cyclists, considering the number of injuries per pedestrian and cyclist, rather than per capita.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has modified its original grid roadway structure through use of diverters and barriers, moving most traffic out of neighborhoods and onto arterial streets (visitors often find this confusing, because the diverters are not shown on all maps).
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley maintains a separate grid of arterial streets for bicycles, called Bicycle Boulevards, with bike lanes and lower amounts of car traffic than the major streets they often parallel.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Attempts to improve the biking infrastructure in Berkeley have been met with controversy.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 2023, the Berkeley city council fired the city's top transportation official for a plan to remove dozens of parking spots on a street to build a protected bike lane.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley hosts car sharing network Zipcar.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Rather than owning (and parking) their own cars, members share a group of cars parked nearby.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Web- and telephone-based reservation systems keep track of hours and charges.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Several "pods" (points of departure where cars are kept) exist throughout the city, in several downtown locations, at the Ashby and North Berkeley BART stations, and at various other locations in Berkeley (and other cities in the region).
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Using alternative transportation is encouraged.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has had recurring problems with parking meter vandalism.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 1999, over 2,400 Berkeley meters were jammed, smashed, or sawed apart.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Starting in 2005 and continuing into 2006, Berkeley began to phase out mechanical meters in favor of more centralized electronic meters.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The Berkeley Branch line was extended from Shattuck and University to Vine Street ("Berryman's Station") in 1878.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Starting in 1882, Berkeley trains ran directly to the Oakland Pier.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In the 1880s, Southern Pacific assumed operations of the Berkeley Branch under a lease from its own paper affiliate, the Northern Railway.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] In 1911, Southern Pacific electrified this line and the several others it constructed in Berkeley, creating its East Bay Electric Lines division.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The huge and heavy cars specially built for these lines were called the "Red Trains" or the "Big Red Cars".
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The Shattuck line was extended and connected with two other Berkeley lines (the Ninth Street Line and the California Street line) at Solano and Colusa (the "Colusa Wye").
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] At this time, the Northbrae Tunnel and Rose Street Undercrossing were constructed, both of which still exist.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] (The Rose Street Undercrossing is not accessible to the public, being situated between what is now two backyards.) The fourth Berkeley line was the Ellsworth St. line to the university campus.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The first electric rail service in Berkeley was provided by several small streetcar companies starting in 1891.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Most of these were eventually bought up by the Key System of Francis "Borax" Smith who added lines and improved equipment.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The Key System's streetcars were operated by its East Bay Street Railways division.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Principal lines in Berkeley ran on Euclid, The Arlington, College, Telegraph, Shattuck, San Pablo, University, and Grove (today's Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The last streetcars ran in 1948, replaced by buses.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The first electric commuter interurban-type trains to San Francisco from Berkeley were put in operation by the Key System in 1903, several years before the Southern Pacific electrified its steam commuter lines.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Like the SP, Key trains ran to a pier serviced by the Key's own fleet of ferryboats, which also docked at the Ferry Building in San Francisco.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] After the Bay Bridge was built, the Key trains ran to the Transbay Terminal in San Francisco, sharing tracks on the lower deck of the Bay Bridge with the SP's red trains and the Sacramento Northern Railroad.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] It was at this time that the Key trains acquired their letter designations, which were later preserved by Key's public successor, AC Transit.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Today's F bus is the successor of the F train.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Before the Bridge, these lines were simply the Shattuck Avenue Line, the Claremont Line, the Westbrae Line, and the Sacramento Street Line, respectively.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] After the Southern Pacific abandoned transbay service in 1941, the Key System acquired the rights to use its tracks and catenary on Shattuck north of Dwight Way and through the Northbrae Tunnel to The Alameda for the F-train.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The SP tracks along Monterey Avenue as far as Colusa had been acquired by the Key System in 1933 for the H-train, but were abandoned in 1941.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] The Key System trains stopped running in April 1958.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] On December 15, 1962, the Northbrae Tunnel was opened to auto traffic.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is the location of a number of nationally prominent businesses, many of which have been pioneers in their areas of operation.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Notable businesses include Chez Panisse, birthplace of California cuisine, Peet's Coffee's original store, the Claremont Resort, punk rock haven 924 Gilman, Saul Zaentz's Fantasy Studios, and Caffe Strada.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Notable former businesses include pioneer bookseller Cody's Books, The Nature Company, The North Face, Clif Bar energy foods, the Berkeley Co-op, and Caffe Mediterraneum.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has relatively few chain stores for a city of its size, due to policies and zoning that promote small businesses and impose limits on the size of certain types of stores.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley has a number of distinct neighborhoods.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Surrounding the University of California campus are the most densely populated parts of the city.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] West of the campus is **Downtown Berkeley**, the city's traditional commercial core; home of the civic center, the city's only public high school, the busiest BART station in Berkeley, as well as a major transfer point for AC Transit buses.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] South of the campus is **Southside**, mainly a student ghetto, where much of the university's student housing is located.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The busiest stretch of Telegraph Avenue is in this neighborhood.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] North of the campus is the quieter **Northside** neighborhood, the location of the Graduate Theological Union.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Farther from the university campus, the influence of the university quickly becomes less visible.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Most of Berkeley's neighborhoods are primarily made up of detached houses, often with separate in-law units in the rear, although larger apartment buildings are also common in many neighborhoods.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Commercial activities are concentrated along the major avenues and at important intersections and frequently define the neighborhood within which they reside.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] In the southeastern corner of the city is the **Claremont District**, home to the Claremont Hotel.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Also in the southeast is the **Elmwood District** known for its commercial area on College Avenue.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] West of Elmwood is **South Berkeley**, known for its weekend flea market at the Ashby Station.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] West of (and including) San Pablo Avenue, itself a major commercial and transport corridor, is **West Berkeley**, the historic commercial center of the city.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] This neighborhood and area includes the former unincorporated town of **Ocean View**.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] West Berkeley contains the remnants of Berkeley's industrial area, much of which has been replaced by retail and office uses, as well as residential live/work loft space, paralleling the decline of manufacturing in the United States.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] This area abuts the shoreline of the San Francisco Bay and is home to the Berkeley Marina.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Also nearby is Berkeley's Aquatic Park, featuring an artificial linear lagoon of San Francisco Bay.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] North of downtown is **North Berkeley** which has its main commercial area nicknamed the "Gourmet Ghetto" because of the concentration of well-known restaurants and other food-related businesses.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] West of North Berkeley (roughly west of Sacramento and north of Cedar) is **Westbrae**, a small neighborhood centered on a small commercial area on Gilman Street and through which part of the Ohlone Greenway runs.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Meanwhile, further north of North Berkeley are **Northbrae**, a master-planned subdivision from the early 20th century, and **Thousand Oaks**.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Above these last three neighborhoods, on the western slopes of the Berkeley Hills are the neighborhoods of **Cragmont** and **La Loma Park**, notable for their dramatic views, winding streets, and numerous public stairways and paths.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The city has many parks, and promotes greenery and the environment.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Tilden Regional Park lies east of the city, occupying the upper extent of Wildcat Canyon between the Berkeley Hills and the San Pablo Ridge.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The city is also heavily involved in creek restoration and wetlands restoration, including a planned *daylighting* of Strawberry Creek along Center Street.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley Marina and East Shore State Park flank its shoreline at San Francisco Bay and organizations like the Urban Creeks Council and Friends of the Five Creeks, the former of which is headquartered in Berkeley, support the riparian areas in the town and coastlines as well.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] César Chávez Park, near the Berkeley Marina, was built at the former site of the city dump.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] 165 buildings in Berkeley are designated as local landmarks or local structures of merit.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley is home to the Chilean-American community's La Peña Cultural Center, the largest cultural center for this community in the United States.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The Freight and Salvage is the oldest established full-time folk and traditional music venue west of the Mississippi River.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Additionally, Berkeley is home to the off-Broadway theater Berkeley Repertory Theater, commonly known as "Berkeley Rep".
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley Repertory Theater consists of two stages, a school, and has received a Tony Award for Outstanding Regional Theatre.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The historic Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive (BAMPFA) is operated by UC Berkeley, and was moved to downtown Berkeley in January 2016.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] It offers many exhibitions and screenings of historic films, as well as outreach programs within the community.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] University of California, Berkeley's main campus is in the city limits.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The Graduate Theological Union, a consortium of eight independent theological schools, is located a block north of the University of California Berkeley's main campus.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The Graduate Theological Union has the largest number of students and faculty of any religious studies doctoral program in the United States.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] In addition to more theological schools, Zaytuna College, a newly established Muslim liberal-arts college, has taken 'Holy Hill' as its new home.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The Institute of Buddhist Studies has been located in Berkeley since 1966.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Wright Institute, a psychology graduate school, is located in Berkeley.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley City College is a community college in the Peralta Community College District.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley Unified School District operates public schools.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The first public school in Berkeley was the Ocean View School, now the site of the Berkeley Adult School located at Virginia Street and San Pablo Avenue.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The public schools today are administered by the Berkeley Unified School District.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] In the 1960s, Berkeley was one of the earliest US cities to voluntarily desegregate, utilizing a system of buses, still in use.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The district has eleven elementary schools and one public high school, Berkeley High School (BHS).
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Established in 1880, BHS currently has over 3,000 students.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley High campus was designated a historic district by the National Register of Historic Places on January 7, 2008.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Saint Mary's College High School, a Catholic school, also has its street address in Berkeley, although most of the grounds and buildings are actually in neighboring Albany.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley has 11 public elementary schools and three middle schools.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The East Bay campus of the German International School of Silicon Valley (GISSV) formerly occupied the Hillside Campus, Berkeley, California; it opened there in 2012.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] In December 2016, the GISSV closed the building, due to unmet seismic retrofit needs.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley Public Library serves as the municipal library.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] University of California, Berkeley Libraries operates the University of California Berkeley libraries.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley has a council–manager government.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The mayor is elected at-large for a four-year term and is the ceremonial head of the city and the chair of the city council.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley City Council is composed of the mayor and eight council members elected by district who each serve four-year terms.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Districts 2, 3, 5 and 6 hold their elections in years divisible by four while Districts 1, 4, 7 and 8 hold theirs in even-numbered years not divisible by four.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The city council appoints a city manager, who is the chief executive of the city.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Additionally, the city voters directly elect an independent city auditor, school board, and rent stabilization board.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Most city officials, including council members, are elected using instant-runoff voting since November 2010.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] In 2014, the City of Berkeley passed a redistricting measure on the ballot to create the nation's first student supermajority district in District 7, which in 2018 elected Rigel Robinson, a 22-year-old UC Berkeley graduate and the youngest Councilmember in the city's history.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] While much of UC Berkeley's student housing is located in District 7, large dormitories also exist in Districts 6 and 8.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The city's Public Health Division is one of four municipally operated public health agencies in California (the other three being Long Beach, Pasadena, and Vernon).
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Though it is part of the city government, it qualifies for the same state funds as a county public health department.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley is also part of Alameda County, for which the Government of Alameda County is defined and authorized under the California Constitution, California law, and the Charter of the County of Alameda.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The county government provides countywide services, such as elections and voter registration, law enforcement, jails, vital records, property records, tax collection, and social services.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The county's health department does not cover the city.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley has been a Democratic stronghold in presidential elections since 1960, becoming one of the most Democratic cities in the country.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The last Republican presidential candidate to receive at least one-quarter of the vote in Berkeley was Richard Nixon in 1968.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Consistent with Berkeley's reputation as a strongly liberal and/or progressive city, in the 2016 presidential election more votes were won by Green Party presidential candidate Jill Stein than by Republican candidate Donald Trump.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] In the 2020 Presidential election, Joe Biden received 93.8% of the vote while Donald Trump received 4.0% of the vote.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] According to the California Secretary of State, as of October 20, 2025, Berkeley has 75,509 registered voters.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Of those, 55,523 (73.53%) are registered Democrats, 2,317 (3.07%) are registered Republicans, 14,323 (18.97%) have declined to state a political party affiliation, and 3,346 (4.43%) are registered with a third party.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley became the first city in the United States to pass a sanctuary resolution on November 8, 1971.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The city had a daily newspaper, the *Berkeley Gazette*, which was founded c.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] The *Berkeley Barb* published counter-culture news from 1965 to 1980.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Current media include *The Daily Californian*, the student newspaper of UC Berkeley; the *Berkeley Times*; and local online-only publications *Berkeleyside*, the *Berkeley Daily Planet*, and *The Berkeley Scanner*.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Notable individuals who were born in and/or have lived in Berkeley include Kamala Harris, Steve Wozniak, scientists J.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Robert Oppenheimer and Ernest Lawrence, actors Ben Affleck, and Andy Samberg, Major League Baseball broadcaster Matt Vasgersian, model Rebecca Romijn, Billie Joe Armstrong, lead singer of Green Day, Adam Duritz of Counting Crows, rapper Lil B, authors Ursula K.
[src:technical-alliance/berkeley-california-p02] Le Guin and Michael Chabon, entertainment and real estate mogul Herbie Herbert, and EDM producer KSHMR, and university presidents Blake R.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Economists, historians, political economists, and sociologists have adopted different perspectives in their analyses of capitalism and have recognized various forms of it in practice.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] These include *laissez-faire* capitalism, free-market capitalism, state capitalism, and welfare capitalism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Different forms of capitalism feature varying degrees of free markets, public ownership, barriers to free competition, and state-sanctioned social policies.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The degree of competition in markets, the role of intervention and regulation, and the scope of state ownership vary across different models of capitalism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The extent to which markets are free and the rules defining private property are matters of politics and policy.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Most of the existing economies in the world today are mixed economies that combine elements of free markets with state intervention and, in some cases, economic planning.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Capitalism in its modern form emerged from agrarianism in England, as well as from mercantilist practices in European countries between the 16th and 18th centuries.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The Industrial Revolution of the 18th century established capitalism as a dominant mode of production characterized by factory work and a complex division of labor.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Through globalization, capitalism spread across the world in the 19th and 20th centuries, especially before World War I and again after the end of the Cold War.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] During the 19th century, capitalism was largely unregulated by the state but became more regulated in the post–World War II period through Keynesianism, followed by a return of more unregulated capitalism termed neoliberalism starting in the 1980s.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The term "capitalist", meaning an owner of capital, appears earlier than the term "capitalism" and dates to the mid-17th century.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] "Capitalism" is derived from *capital*, which evolved from *capitale*, a late Latin word based on *caput*, meaning "head"—which is also the origin of "chattel" and "cattle" in the sense of movable property (only much later to refer only to livestock).
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] *Capitale* emerged in the 12th to 13th centuries to refer to funds, stock of merchandise, sum of money or money carrying interest.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] By 1283, it was used in the sense of the capital assets of a trading firm and was often interchanged with other words—wealth, money, funds, goods, assets, property and so on.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The *Hollantse Mercurius* (1651-1691) uses "capitalists" in 1653 and 1654 to refer to owners of capital.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In French, Étienne Clavier referred to *capitalistes* in 1788, four years before its first recorded English usage by Arthur Young in his work *Travels in France* (1792).
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In his *Principles of Political Economy and Taxation* (1817), David Ricardo referred to "the capitalist" many times.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] English poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge used "capitalist" in his work *Table Talk* (1823).
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Pierre-Joseph Proudhon used the term in his first work, *What is Property?* (1840), to refer to the owners of capital.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Benjamin Disraeli used the term in his 1845 work *Sybil*.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Alexander Hamilton used "capitalist" in his Report of Manufactures presented to the United States Congress in 1791.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Karl Marx frequently referred to the "capital" and to the "capitalist mode of production" in *Das Kapital* (1867).
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Marx did not use the form *capitalism* but instead used capital, *capitalist* and *capitalist mode of production*, which appear frequently.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Due to the word being coined by socialist critics of capitalism, economist and historian Robert Hessen stated that the term "capitalism" itself is a term of disparagement and a misnomer for economic individualism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Bernard Harcourt agrees with the statement that the term is a misnomer, adding that it misleadingly suggests that there is such a thing as "capital" that inherently functions in certain ways and is governed by stable economic laws of its own.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In the English language, the term "capitalism" first appears, according to the *Oxford English Dictionary* (OED), in 1854, in the novel *The Newcomes* by novelist William Makepeace Thackeray, where the word meant "having ownership of capital".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Also according to the OED, Carl Adolph Douai, a German American socialist and abolitionist, used the term "private capitalism" in 1863.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] There is no universally agreed upon definition of capitalism; it is unclear whether or not capitalism characterizes an entire society, a specific type of social order, or crucial components or elements of a society.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Societies officially founded in opposition to capitalism, such as the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics (U.S.S.R), and the People's Republic of China, have sometimes been argued to actually exhibit characteristics of capitalism, despite the denouncement from their claimed communist ideology.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Nancy Fraser describes usage of the term "capitalism" by many authors as "mainly rhetorical, functioning less as an actual concept than as a gesture toward the need for a concept".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Scholars who are uncritical of capitalism rarely actually use the term "capitalism".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Some doubt that the term "capitalism" possesses valid scientific dignity, and it is generally not discussed in mainstream economics, with economist Daron Acemoglu suggesting that the term "capitalism" should be abandoned entirely.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Consequently, understanding of the concept of capitalism tends to be heavily influenced by opponents of capitalism and by the followers and critics of Karl Marx.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Capitalism, in its modern form, can be traced to the emergence of agrarian capitalism and mercantilism in the early Renaissance, in city-states like Florence.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Capital has existed incipiently on a small scale for centuries in the form of merchant, renting and lending activities and occasionally as small-scale industry with some wage labor.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Simple commodity exchange and consequently simple commodity production, which is the initial basis for the growth of capital from trade, have a very long history.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] During the Islamic Golden Age, Arabs promulgated capitalist economic policies such as free trade and banking.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Their use of Indo-Arabic numerals facilitated bookkeeping.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] These innovations migrated to Europe through trade partners in cities such as Venice and Pisa.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Italian mathematicians traveled the Mediterranean talking to Arab traders and returned to popularize the use of Indo-Arabic numerals in Europe.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The economic foundations of the feudal agricultural system began to shift substantially in 16th-century England as the manorial system had broken down and land began to become concentrated in the hands of fewer landlords with increasingly large estates.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Instead of a serf-based system of labor, workers were increasingly employed as part of a broader and expanding money-based economy.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Terms of rent for land were becoming subject to economic market forces rather than to the previous stagnant system of custom and feudal obligation.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The economic doctrine prevailing from the 16th to the 18th centuries is commonly called mercantilism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] This period, the Age of Discovery, was associated with the geographic exploration of foreign lands by merchant traders, especially from England and the Low Countries.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Mercantilism was a system of trade for profit, although commodities were still largely produced by non-capitalist methods.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Most scholars consider the era of merchant capitalism and mercantilism as the origin of modern capitalism, although Karl Polanyi argued that the hallmark of capitalism is the establishment of generalized markets for what he called the "fictitious commodities", i.e. land, labor and money.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Accordingly, he argued that "not until 1834 was a competitive labor market established in England, hence industrial capitalism as a social system cannot be said to have existed before that date".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] England began a large-scale and integrative approach to mercantilism during the Elizabethan Era (1558–1603).
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] A systematic and coherent explanation of balance of trade was made public through Thomas Mun's argument *England's Treasure by Forraign Trade, or the Balance of our Forraign Trade is The Rule of Our Treasure.* It was written in the 1620s and published in 1664.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] European merchants, backed by state controls, subsidies and monopolies, made most of their profits by buying and selling goods.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In the words of Francis Bacon, the purpose of mercantilism was "the opening and well-balancing of trade; the cherishing of manufacturers; the banishing of idleness; the repressing of waste and excess by sumptuary laws; the improvement and husbanding of the soil; the regulation of prices...".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] After the period of the proto-industrialization, the British East India Company and the Dutch East India Company, after massive contributions from the Mughal Bengal, inaugurated an expansive era of commerce and trade.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] These companies were characterized by their colonial and expansionary powers given to them by nation-states.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] During this era, merchants, who had traded under the previous stage of mercantilism, invested capital in the East India Companies and other colonies, seeking a return on investment.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In the mid-18th century a group of economic theorists, led by David Hume (1711–1776) and Adam Smith (1723–1790), challenged fundamental mercantilist doctrines—such as the belief that the world's wealth remained constant and that a state could only increase its wealth at the expense of another state.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] During the Industrial Revolution, industrialists replaced merchants as a dominant factor in the capitalist system and effected the decline of the traditional handicraft skills of artisans, guilds, and journeymen.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Industrial capitalism marked the development of the factory system of manufacturing, characterized by a complex division of labor between and within work process and the routine of work tasks; and eventually established the domination of the capitalist mode of production.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Industrial Britain eventually abandoned the protectionist policy formerly prescribed by mercantilism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In the 19th century, Richard Cobden (1804–1865) and John Bright (1811–1889), who based their beliefs on the Manchester School, initiated a movement to lower tariffs.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In the 1840s Britain adopted a less protectionist policy, with the 1846 repeal of the Corn Laws and the 1849 repeal of the Navigation Acts.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Britain reduced tariffs and quotas, in line with David Ricardo's advocacy of free trade.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Broader processes of globalization carried capitalism across the world.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] By the beginning of the nineteenth century, a series of loosely connected market systems had come together as a relatively integrated global system, in turn intensifying processes of economic and other globalization.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Late in the 20th century, capitalism overcame a challenge by centrally-planned economies and is now the encompassing system worldwide, with the mixed economy as its dominant form in the industrialized Western world.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Industrialization allowed cheap production of household items using economies of scale, while rapid population growth created sustained demand for commodities.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The imperialism of the 18th-century decisively shaped globalization.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] After the First and Second Opium Wars (1839–1860) by Britain and France and the completion of the British conquest of India by 1858 and the French conquest of Africa, Polynesia and Indochina by 1887, vast populations of Asia became consumers of European exports.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Europeans colonized areas of Africa and the Pacific islands.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] From the 1870s to the early 1920s, the global financial system was mainly tied to the gold standard.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The United Kingdom first formally adopted this standard in 1821.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Soon to follow were Canada in 1853, Newfoundland in 1865, the United States and Germany (*de jure*) in 1873.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] New technologies such as the telegraph, transatlantic cable, radiotelephone, steamships, and railways allowed goods and information to move around the world to an unprecedented degree.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In the United States, until the 1920s, the term "capitalist" primarily referred to powerful businessmen due to widespread societal skepticism and criticism of capitalism and its most ardent supporters.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Contemporary capitalist societies developed in the West from 1950 to the present and this type of system continues throughout the world—relevant examples started in the United States after the 1950s, France after the 1960s, Spain after the 1970s, Poland after 2015, and others.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] At this stage most capitalist markets are considered developed and characterized by developed private and public markets for equity and debt, a high standard of living (as characterized by the World Bank and the IMF), large institutional investors and a well-funded banking system.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] A significant managerial class has emerged and decides on a significant proportion of investments and other decisions.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The postwar boom ended in the late 1960s and early 1970s and the economic situation grew worse with the rise of stagflation.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Monetarism, a modification of Keynesianism that is more compatible with *laissez-faire* analyses, gained increasing prominence in the capitalist world, especially under the years in office of Ronald Reagan in the United States (1981–1989) and of Margaret Thatcher in the United Kingdom (1979–1990).
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Public and political interest began shifting away from the so-called collectivist concerns of Keynes's managed capitalism to a focus on individual choice, called "remarketized capitalism".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The end of the Cold War and the dissolution of the Soviet Union allowed for capitalism to become a truly global system in a way not seen since before World War I.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The development of the neoliberal global economy would have been impossible without the fall of communism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The relationship between democracy and capitalism is a contentious area in theory and in popular political movements.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The extension of adult-male suffrage in 19th-century Britain occurred along with the development of industrial capitalism and representative democracy became widespread at the same time as capitalism, leading capitalists to posit a causal or mutual relationship between them.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] However, according to some authors in the 20th-century, capitalism also accompanied a variety of political formations quite distinct from liberal democracies, including fascist regimes, absolute monarchies and single-party states.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Democratic peace theory asserts that democracies seldom fight other democracies, but others suggest this may be because of political similarity or stability, rather than because they are "democratic" or "capitalist".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Critics argue that though economic growth under capitalism has led to democracy, it may not do so in the future as authoritarian régimes have been able to manage economic growth using some of capitalism's competitive principles without making concessions to greater political freedom.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Political scientists Torben Iversen and David Soskice see democracy and capitalism as mutually supportive.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Robert Dahl argued in *On Democracy* that capitalism was beneficial for democracy because economic growth and a large middle class were good for democracy.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] He also argued that a market economy provided a substitute for government control of the economy, which reduces the risks of tyranny and authoritarianism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In his book *The Road to Serfdom* (1944), Friedrich Hayek (1899–1992) asserted that the free-market understanding of economic freedom as present in capitalism is a requisite of political freedom.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] He argued that the market mechanism is the only way of deciding what to produce and how to distribute the items without using coercion.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Milton Friedman and Ronald Reagan also promoted this view.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Friedman claimed that centralized economic operations are always accompanied by political repression.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In his view, transactions in a market economy are voluntary and the wide diversity that voluntary activity permits is a fundamental threat to repressive political leaders and greatly diminishes their power to coerce.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Some of Friedman's views were shared by John Maynard Keynes, who believed that capitalism was vital for freedom to survive and thrive.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] According to Clara Mattei, capitalism and democracy are "fundamentally incompatible" as real democracy requires a modicum of economic agency, which capitalism inherently undermines by making the majority of people dependent on selling their labor for survival.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] States with capitalistic economic systems have thrived under political regimes deemed to be authoritarian or oppressive.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Singapore has a successful open market economy as a result of its competitive, business-friendly climate and robust rule of law.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Nonetheless, it often comes under fire for its style of government which, though democratic and consistently one of the least corrupt, operates largely under a one-party rule.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Furthermore, it does not vigorously defend freedom of expression as evidenced by its government-regulated press, and its penchant for upholding laws protecting ethnic and religious harmony, judicial dignity and personal reputation.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The private (capitalist) sector in the People's Republic of China has grown exponentially and thrived since its inception, despite having an authoritarian government.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Augusto Pinochet's rule in Chile led to economic growth and high levels of inequality by using authoritarian means to create a safe environment for investment and capitalism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Similarly, Suharto's authoritarian reign and extirpation of the Communist Party of Indonesia allowed for the expansion of capitalism in Indonesia.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The term "capitalism" in its modern sense is often attributed to Karl Marx.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In *Das Kapital*, Marx analyzed the "capitalist mode of production" using a method of critique that later became known as Marxism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] However, while Marx did discuss capitalism extensively, he used the term "capitalism" less frequently than "capitalist mode of production".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] His collaborator, Friedrich Engels, played a significant role in popularizing the term in more political interpretations of their work.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In the 20th century, supporters of the capitalist system often replaced the term "capitalism" with phrases such as "free enterprise" or "private enterprise" to avoid its negative connotations.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Similarly, the term "capitalist" was sometimes substituted with "investor" or "entrepreneur" to emphasize productive roles rather than passive wealth accumulation.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In free market and *laissez-faire* forms of capitalism, markets are used most extensively with minimal or no regulation over the pricing mechanism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In mixed economies, which are almost universal today, markets continue to play a dominant role, but they are regulated to some extent by the state in order to correct market failures, promote social welfare, conserve natural resources, fund defense and public safety or other rationale.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In state capitalist systems, markets are relied upon the least, with the state relying heavily on state-owned enterprises or indirect economic planning to accumulate capital.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Competition arises when more than one producer is trying to sell the same or similar products to the same buyers.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Adherents of the capitalist theory believe that competition leads to innovation and more affordable prices.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Monopolies or cartels can develop, especially if there is no competition.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] A monopoly occurs when a firm has exclusivity over a market.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Hence, the firm can engage in rent seeking behaviors such as limiting output and raising prices because it has no fear of competition.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Governments have implemented legislation for the purpose of preventing the creation of monopolies and cartels.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In 1890, the Sherman Antitrust Act became the first legislation passed by the United States Congress to limit monopolies.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Wage labor, usually referred to as paid work, paid employment, or paid labor, refers to the socioeconomic relationship between a worker and an employer in which the worker sells their labor power under a formal or informal employment contract.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] "All labor contracts were/are designed legally to bind a worker in one way or another to fulfill the labor obligations the worker has undertaken.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] That is one of the principal purposes of labor contracts." These transactions usually occur in a labor market where wages or salaries are market-determined.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In exchange for the money paid as wages (usual for short-term work-contracts) or salaries (in permanent employment contracts), the work product generally becomes the undifferentiated property of the employer.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] A wage laborer is a person whose primary means of income is from the selling of their labor in this way.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The profit motive, in the theory of capitalism, is the desire to earn income in the form of profit.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Stated differently, the reason for a business's existence is to turn a profit.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The profit motive functions according to rational choice theory, or the theory that individuals tend to pursue what is in their own best interests.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Accordingly, businesses seek to benefit themselves and/or their shareholders by maximizing profit.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In capitalist theoretics, the profit motive is said to ensure that resources are being allocated efficiently.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Socialist theorists note that, unlike mercantilists, capitalists accumulate their profits while expecting their profit rates to remain the same.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] This causes problems as earnings in the rest of society do not increase in the same proportion.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The relationship between the state, its formal mechanisms, and capitalist societies has been debated in many fields of social and political theory, with active discussion since the 19th century.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Hernando de Soto is a contemporary Peruvian economist who has argued that an important characteristic of capitalism is the functioning state protection of property rights in a formal property system where ownership and transactions are clearly recorded.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] According to de Soto, this is the process by which physical assets are transformed into capital, which in turn may be used in many more ways and much more efficiently in the market economy.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] A number of Marxian economists have argued that the inclosure acts in England and similar legislation elsewhere were an integral part of capitalist primitive accumulation and that specific legal frameworks of private land ownership have been integral to the development of capitalism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Private property rights are not absolute, as in many countries the state has the power to seize private property, typically for public use, under the powers of eminent domain.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In capitalist economics, market competition is the rivalry among sellers trying to achieve such goals as increasing profits, market share and sales volume by varying the elements of the marketing mix: price, product, distribution and promotion.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Merriam-Webster defines competition in business as "the effort of two or more parties acting independently to secure the business of a third party by offering the most favourable terms".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] It was described by Adam Smith in *The Wealth of Nations* (1776) and later economists as allocating productive resources to their most highly valued uses and encouraging efficiency.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Smith and other classical economists before Antoine Augustine Cournot were referring to price and non-price rivalry among producers to sell their goods on best terms by bidding of buyers, not necessarily to a large number of sellers nor to a market in final equilibrium.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Competition is widespread throughout the market process.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] It is a condition where "buyers tend to compete with other buyers, and sellers tend to compete with other sellers".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In offering goods for exchange, buyers competitively bid to purchase specific quantities of specific goods which are available, or might be available if sellers were to choose to offer such goods.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Similarly, sellers bid against other sellers in offering goods on the market, competing for the attention and exchange resources of buyers.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Competition results from scarcity, as it is not possible to satisfy all conceivable human wants, and occurs as people try to meet the criteria being used to determine allocation.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In the works of Adam Smith, the idea of capitalism is made possible through competition which creates growth.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Although capitalism had not entered mainstream economics at the time of Smith, it is vital to the construction of his ideal society.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] One of the foundational blocks of capitalism is competition.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Smith believed that a prosperous society is one where "everyone should be free to enter and leave the market and change trades as often as he pleases." He believed that the freedom to act in one's self-interest is essential for the success of a capitalist society.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Instead, Smith maintained that they should focus on personal progress instead and that this will result in overall growth to the whole.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Economic growth is a characteristic tendency of capitalist economies.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] However, capitalist economies may experience fluctuations in growth that cannot be accounted for by demographic or technological changes.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] These fluctuations, which involve sustained periods of economic growth and recession, are referred to as business cycles in macroeconomics.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Economic growth is measured as growth in investment, economic output, and economic consumption per capita.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Changes in hours of employment on their own are not considered as a factor of economic growth.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The capitalist mode of production refers to the systems of organising production and distribution within capitalist societies.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Private money-making in various forms (renting, banking, merchant trade, production for profit and so on) preceded the development of the capitalist mode of production as such.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The term capitalist mode of production is defined by private ownership of the means of production, extraction of surplus value by the owning class for the purpose of capital accumulation, wage-based labor and, at least as far as commodities are concerned, being market-based.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Capitalism in the form of money-making activity has existed in the shape of merchants and money-lenders who acted as intermediaries between consumers and producers engaging in simple commodity production (hence the reference to "merchant capitalism") since the beginnings of civilisation.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] What is specific about the "capitalist mode of production" is that most of the inputs and outputs of production are supplied through the market (i.e. they are commodities) and essentially all production is in this mode.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] By contrast, in flourishing feudalism most or all of the factors of production, including labor, are owned by the feudal ruling class outright and the products may also be consumed without a market of any kind, it is production for use within the feudal social unit and for limited trade.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Essentially, capital accumulation comes to define economic rationality in capitalist production.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] A society, region or nation is capitalist if the predominant source of incomes and products being distributed is capitalist activity, but even so this does not yet mean necessarily that the capitalist mode of production is dominant in that society.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Mixed economies rely on the nation they are in to provide some goods or services, while the free market produces and maintains the rest.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Government agencies regulate the standards of service in many industries, such as airlines and broadcasting, as well as financing a wide range of programs.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In addition, the government regulates the flow of capital and uses financial tools such as the interest rate to control such factors as inflation and unemployment.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In capitalist economic structures, supply and demand is an economic model of price determination in a market.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] If demand decreases (demand curve shifts to the left) and supply remains unchanged, then a surplus occurs, leading to a lower equilibrium price.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] If demand remains unchanged and supply increases (supply curve shifts to the right), then a surplus occurs, leading to a lower equilibrium price.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] If demand remains unchanged and supply decreases (supply curve shifts to the left), then a shortage occurs, leading to a higher equilibrium price.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] A supply schedule is a table that shows the relationship between the price of a good and the quantity supplied.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] According to the law of demand, the demand curve is almost always represented as downward sloping, meaning that as price decreases, consumers will buy more of the good.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Just like the supply curves reflect marginal cost curves, demand curves are determined by marginal utility curves.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In the context of supply and demand, economic equilibrium refers to a state where economic forces such as supply and demand are balanced and in the absence of external influences the (equilibrium) values of economic variables will not change.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] For example, in the standard text-book model of perfect competition equilibrium occurs at the point at which quantity demanded and quantity supplied are equal.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Market equilibrium, in this case, refers to a condition where a market price is established through competition such that the amount of goods or services sought by buyers is equal to the amount of goods or services produced by sellers.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] This price is often called the competitive price or market clearing price and will tend not to change unless demand or supply changes.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Partial equilibrium, as the name suggests, takes into consideration only a part of the market to attain equilibrium.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Jain proposes (attributed to George Stigler): "A partial equilibrium is one which is based on only a restricted range of data, a standard example is price of a single product, the prices of all other products being held fixed during the analysis".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] Hosseini, the "power of supply and demand" was discussed to some extent by several early Muslim scholars, such as fourteenth century Mamluk scholar Ibn Taymiyyah, who wrote: "If desire for goods increases while its availability decreases, its price rises.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] On the other hand, if availability of the good increases and the desire for it decreases, the price comes down".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] John Locke's 1691 work *Some Considerations on the Consequences of the Lowering of Interest and the Raising of the Value of Money* includes an early and clear description of supply and demand and their relationship.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In this description, demand is rent: "The price of any commodity rises or falls by the proportion of the number of buyer and sellers" and "that which regulates the price... [of goods] is nothing else but their quantity in proportion to their rent".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] David Ricardo titled one chapter of his 1817 work *Principles of Political Economy and Taxation* "On the Influence of Demand and Supply on Price".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] In *Principles of Political Economy and Taxation*, Ricardo more rigorously laid down the idea of the assumptions that were used to build his ideas of supply and demand.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p01] The model was further developed and popularized by Alfred Marshall in the 1890 textbook *Principles of Economics*.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] There are many variants of capitalism in existence that differ according to country and region.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] They vary in their institutional makeup and by their economic policies.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] The common features among all the different forms of capitalism are that they are predominantly based on the private ownership of the means of production and the production of goods and services for profit; the market-based allocation of resources; and the accumulation of capital.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] They include advanced capitalism, corporate capitalism, finance capitalism, free-market capitalism, mercantilism, state capitalism and welfare capitalism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Other theoretical variants of capitalism include anarcho-capitalism, community capitalism, humanistic capitalism, neo-capitalism, state monopoly capitalism, and technocapitalism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Advanced capitalism is the situation that pertains to a society in which the capitalist model has been integrated and developed deeply and extensively for a prolonged period.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Various writers identify Antonio Gramsci as an influential early theorist of advanced capitalism, even if he did not use the term himself.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] In his writings, Gramsci sought to explain how capitalism had adapted to avoid the revolutionary overthrow that had seemed inevitable in the 19th century.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] At the heart of his explanation was the decline of raw coercion as a tool of class power, replaced by use of civil society institutions to manipulate public ideology in the capitalists' favour.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Jürgen Habermas has been a major contributor to the analysis of advanced-capitalistic societies.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Constant reliance on the state to stabilise the economic system.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] A formally democratic government that legitimises the activities of the state and dissipates opposition to the system.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] The use of nominal wage increases to pacify the most restless segments of the work force.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Corporate capitalism is a free or mixed-market capitalist economy characterized by the dominance of hierarchical and bureaucratic corporations.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Finance capitalism is the subordination of processes of production to the accumulation of money profits in a financial system.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] In their critique of capitalism, Marxism and Leninism both emphasise the role of finance capital as the determining and ruling-class interest in capitalist society, particularly in the latter stages.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Lenin concluded that the banks at that time operated as "the chief nerve centres of the whole capitalist system of national economy".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] For the Comintern (founded in 1919), the phrase "dictatorship of finance capitalism" became a regular one.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Fernand Braudel would later point to two earlier periods when finance capitalism had emerged in human history—with the Genoese in the 16th century and with the Dutch in the 17th and 18th centuries—although at those points it developed from commercial capitalism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Giovanni Arrighi extended Braudel's analysis to suggest that a predominance of finance capitalism is a recurring, long-term phenomenon, whenever a previous phase of commercial/industrial capitalist expansion reaches a plateau.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] A capitalist free-market economy is an economic system where prices for goods and services are set entirely by the forces of supply and demand and are expected, by its adherents, to reach their point of equilibrium without intervention by government policy.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] It typically entails support for highly competitive markets and private ownership of the means of production.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] *Laissez-faire* capitalism is a more extensive form of this free-market economy, but one in which the role of the state is limited to protecting property rights.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] In anarcho-capitalist theory, property rights are protected by private firms and market-generated law.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] According to anarcho-capitalists, this entails property rights without statutory law through market-generated tort, contract and property law, and self-sustaining private industry.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Mercantilism is a nationalist form of early capitalism that came into existence approximately in the late 16th century.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] It is characterized by the intertwining of national business interests with state-interest and imperialism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Consequently, the state apparatus is used to advance national business interests abroad.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] An example of this is colonists living in America who were only allowed to trade with and purchase goods from their respective mother countries (e.g., United Kingdom, France and Portugal).
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Mercantilism was driven by the belief that the wealth of a nation is increased through a positive balance of trade with other nations—it corresponds to the phase of capitalist development sometimes called the primitive accumulation of capital.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] This model is prominent in Western and Northern European countries as well as Japan, albeit in slightly different configurations.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] The vast majority of enterprises are privately owned in this economic model.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Rhine capitalism is the contemporary model of capitalism and adaptation of the social market model that exists in continental Western Europe today.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] State capitalism is a market economy dominated by state-owned enterprises, where the state enterprises are organized as commercial, profit-seeking businesses.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] The designation has been used broadly during parts of the 20th and 21st centuries, especially in a few of the former Eastern Bloc countries such as Yugoslavia.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] According to Aldo Musacchio, a professor at Harvard Business School, state capitalism is a system in which governments exercise a widespread influence on the economy either through direct ownership or subsidies.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Contemporary state capitalism is associated with the East Asian model of capitalism, dirigisme, and the economy of Norway.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Alternatively, Merriam-Webster defines state capitalism as "an economic system in which private capitalism is modified by a varying degree of government ownership and control".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] In his writings, Vladimir Lenin characterized the economy of Soviet Russia as state capitalist, believing state capitalism to be an early step toward the development of socialism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Some economists and left-wing academics including Richard D.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Wolff and some Marxist philosophers such as Raya Dunayevskaya and C.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] James, argue that the economies of the former Soviet Union and Eastern Bloc represented a form of state capitalism because their internal organization within enterprises and the system of wage labor remained intact.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] The term is not used by Austrian School economists to describe state ownership of the means of production.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] The economist Ludwig von Mises argued that the designation of state capitalism was a new label for the old labels of state socialism and planned economy and differed only in non-essentials from these earlier designations.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Political capitalism or Politically oriented capitalism is a term coined by Max Weber in his 1921 book *Economy and Society* to describe monetary profit-making through non-market means.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Holcombe described political capitalism as an economic system in which the sharp distinction between states and markets is blurred.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Welfare capitalism is capitalism that includes social welfare policies.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Today, welfare capitalism is most often associated with the models of capitalism found in Central and Northern Europe such as the Nordic model, social market economy and Rhine capitalism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] In some cases, welfare capitalism exists within a mixed economy, but welfare states can and do exist independently of policies common to mixed economies such as state interventionism and extensive regulation.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] A mixed economy is a largely market-based capitalist economy consisting of both private and public ownership of the means of production and economic interventionism through macroeconomic policies intended to correct market failures, reduce unemployment and keep inflation low.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] The degree of intervention in markets varies among different countries.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Some mixed economies such as France under dirigisme also featured a degree of indirect economic planning over a largely capitalist-based economy.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Most modern capitalist economies are defined as mixed economies to some degree, however French economist Thomas Piketty stated in 2013 that capitalist economies might shift to a much more *laissez-faire* approach in the near future.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Eco-capitalism, also known as "environmental capitalism" or (sometimes) "green capitalism", is the view that capital exists in nature as "natural capital" (ecosystems that have ecological yield) on which all wealth depends.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Therefore, governments should use market-based policy instruments (such as a carbon tax) to resolve environmental problems.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Sustainable capitalism is a conceptual form of capitalism based upon sustainable practices that seek to preserve humanity and the planet, while reducing externalities and bearing a resemblance of capitalist economic policy.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] A capitalistic economy must expand to survive and find new markets to support this expansion.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Capitalist systems are often destructive to the environment as well as certain individuals without access to proper representation.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] However, sustainability provides quite the opposite; it implies not only a continuation, but a replenishing of resources.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Sustainability is often thought of to be related to environmentalism, and sustainable capitalism applies sustainable principles to economic governance and social aspects of capitalism as well.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] The importance of sustainable capitalism has been more recently recognized, but the concept is not new.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Changes to the current economic model would have heavy social environmental and economic implications and require the efforts of individuals, as well as compliance of local, state and federal governments.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Controversy surrounds the concept as it requires an increase in sustainable practices and a marked decrease in current consumptive behaviors.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] This is a concept of capitalism described in Al Gore and David Blood's manifesto for the Generation Investment Management to describe a long-term political, economic and social structure which would mitigate current threats to the planet and society.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] According to their manifesto, sustainable capitalism would integrate the environmental, social and governance (ESG) aspects into risk assessment in attempt to limit externalities.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Most of the ideas they list are related to economic changes, and social aspects, but strikingly few are explicitly related to any environmental policy change.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] The accumulation of capital is the process of "making money" or growing an initial sum of money through investment in production.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Capitalism is based on the accumulation of capital, whereby financial capital is invested in order to make a profit and then reinvested into further production in a continuous process of accumulation.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] In Marxian economic theory, this dynamic is called the law of value.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Capital accumulation forms the basis of capitalism, where economic activity is structured around the accumulation of capital, defined as investment in order to realize a financial profit.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] In this context, "capital" is defined as money or a financial asset invested for the purpose of making more money (whether in the form of profit, rent, interest, royalties, capital gain or some other kind of return).
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] In mainstream economics, accounting and Marxian economics, capital accumulation is often equated with investment of profit income or savings, especially in real capital goods.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] The concentration and centralisation of capital are two of the results of such accumulation.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] In modern macroeconomics and econometrics, the phrase "capital formation" is often used in preference to "accumulation", though the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) refers nowadays to "accumulation".
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] The term "accumulation" is occasionally used in national accounts.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Wage labor refers to the sale of labor under a formal or informal employment contract to an employer.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] These transactions usually occur in a labor market where wages are market determined.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] In Marxist economics, these owners of the means of production and suppliers of capital are generally called capitalists.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] The description of the role of the capitalist has shifted, first referring to a useless intermediary between producers, then to an employer of producers, and finally to the owners of the means of production.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Labor includes all physical and mental human resources, including entrepreneurial capacity and management skills, which are required to produce products and services.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Production is the act of making goods or services by applying labor power.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Criticism of capitalism comes from various political and philosophical approaches, including anarchist, socialist, religious and nationalist viewpoints.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Of those who oppose it or want to modify it, some believe that capitalism should be removed through revolution while others believe that it should be changed slowly through political reforms.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Other critics argue that inequities are not due to the ethic-neutral construct of the economic system commonly known as capitalism, but to the ethics of those who shape and execute the system.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] For example, some contend that Milton Friedman's ethic of 'maximizing shareholder value' creates a harmful form of capitalism, while Millard Fuller's or John Bogle's ethic of 'enough' creates a sustainable form.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Equitable ethics and unified ethical decision-making is theorized to create a less damaging form of capitalism.
[src:technical-alliance/capitalism-p02] Inheritance has been argued to not be a fundamental part of capitalism, instead being a form of nepotism.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] At the time of his death, Steinmetz held over 200 patents.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A genius in both mathematics and electronics, he did work that earned him the nicknames "Forger of Thunderbolts" and "The Wizard of Schenectady".
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz was born Karl August Rudolph Steinmetz on April 9, 1865, in Breslau, Province of Silesia, Prussia (now Wrocław, Poland), the son of Caroline (Neubert) and Karl Heinrich Steinmetz.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He was baptized as a Lutheran into the Evangelical Church of Prussia.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz, who stood only 4 ft 0 in (1.22 m) tall as an adult, had dwarfism, hunchback, and hip dysplasia, as did his father and grandfather.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz graduated with honors from St.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Following Gymnasium, Steinmetz studied at the University of Breslau to begin work on his undergraduate degree in 1883.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Nearing completion of his doctorate in 1888, he was forced to flee to Zurich, Switzerland, as the German government was preparing to prosecute him for his socialist activities.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] As socialist meetings and press had been banned in Germany, Steinmetz fled to Zurich in 1889 to escape possible arrest.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Faced with an expiring visa, he emigrated to the United States in 1889 at the age of 24.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He changed his first name to "Charles" to sound more American, and chose the middle name "Proteus", a wise hunchbacked character from the *Odyssey* who knew many secrets, after an epithet bestowed upon him by his college fraternity brothers.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz was politically active in the US as a technocratic socialist for over thirty years.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Following the Bolshevik introduction of a technocratic plan to electrify Russia, Steinmetz spoke of Lenin alongside Albert Einstein as the "two greatest minds of our time." He believed in a corporatist industrial government also covering its human welfare function.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A member of the original Technical Alliance, which also included Thorstein Veblen and Leland Olds, Steinmetz had great faith in the ability of machines to eliminate human toil and create abundance for all.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He put it this way: "Some day we [will] make the good things of life for everybody." Steinmetz's techno-utopian optimism was deeply intertwined with his political beliefs, and he was convinced that the spread of electrification would inevitably steer human society toward socialism.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz is known for his contribution in three major fields of alternating current (AC) systems theory: hysteresis, steady-state analysis, and transients.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Shortly after arriving in the United States, Steinmetz went to work for Rudolf Eickemeyer in Yonkers, New York, and published in the field of magnetic hysteresis, earning worldwide professional recognition.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Eickemeyer's firm developed transformers for use in the transmission of electrical power among many other mechanical and electrical devices.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In 1893 Eickemeyer's company, along with all of its patents and designs, was bought by the newly formed General Electric Company, where Steinmetz quickly became known as the engineering wizard in GE's engineering community.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz's work revolutionized AC circuit theory and analysis, which had been carried out using complicated, time-consuming calculus-based methods.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In the groundbreaking paper, "Complex Quantities and Their Use in Electrical Engineering", presented at a July 1893 meeting published in the American Institute of Electrical Engineers (AIEE), Steinmetz simplified these complicated methods to "a simple problem of algebra".
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He systematized the use of complex number phasor representation in electrical engineering education texts, whereby the lower-case letter "j" is used to designate the 90-degree rotation operator in AC system analysis.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] His seminal books and many other AIEE papers "taught a whole generation of engineers how to deal with AC phenomena".
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz also greatly advanced the understanding of lightning.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] His systematic experiments resulted in the first laboratory-created "man-made lightning", earning him the nickname "Forger of Thunderbolts".
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] These were conducted in a football-field-sized laboratory at General Electric, using 120 000-volt generators.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Like alternating-current pioneer Nikola Tesla, he also erected a lightning tower to attract natural lightning to study its patterns and effects, which resulted in several theories.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He was granted an honorary degree from Harvard University in 1901 and a doctorate from Union College in 1903.; other awards include the Certificate of Merit of Franklin Institute, 1908; the Elliott Cresson Medal, 1913; and the Cedergren Medal, 1914.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz was also an elected member of both the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and the American Philosophical Society.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz wrote 13 books and 60 articles, not exclusively about engineering.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He was a member and adviser to the fraternity Phi Gamma Delta at Union College, whose chapter house was one of the first electrified residences.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] While serving as president of the Schenectady Board of Education, Steinmetz introduced numerous progressive reforms, including extended school hours, school meals, school nurses, special classes for the children of immigrants, and the distribution of free textbooks.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz had dwarfism, standing only 4 ft 0 in (1.22 m) tall as an adult, and was affected by kyphosis like his father and grandfather.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In spite of his love for children and family life, Steinmetz remained unmarried, to prevent his spinal deformity from being passed to any offspring.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] When Joseph LeRoy Hayden, a loyal and hardworking lab assistant, announced that he would marry and look for his own living quarters, Steinmetz made the unusual proposal of opening his large home, complete with research lab, greenhouse, and office to the Haydens and their prospective family.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Hayden favored the idea, but his future wife was wary of the unorthodox arrangement.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] She agreed after Steinmetz's assurance that she could run the house as she saw fit.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] After an uneasy start, the arrangement worked well for all parties, especially after three Hayden children were born.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz legally adopted Joseph Hayden as his son, becoming grandfather to the youngsters, entertaining them with fantastic stories and spectacular scientific demonstrations.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] The unusual, harmonious living arrangement lasted for the rest of Steinmetz's life.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In 1894, Steinmetz founded the *Mohawk Aerial Navigation Company (Ltd.)*, which became the first practical, active gliding club in the world.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He died on October 26, 1923, at the age of 58 and was buried in Vale Cemetery in Schenectady.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz earned wide recognition among the scientific community and numerous awards and honors both during his life and posthumously.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz's equation, derived from his experiments, defines the approximate heat energy due to magnetic hysteresis released, per cycle per unit volume of magnetic material.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A Steinmetz solid is the solid body generated by the intersection of two or three cylinders of equal radius at right angles.
[src:technical-alliance/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz's equivalent circuit is still widely used for the design and testing of induction machines.
